(140, NULL, '<p>Calisthenics</p><p> The oldest form of resistance training </p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A) Calisthenics has endured and thrived because of its simplicity and utility, from the first caveman to scale a tree or hang from a cliff face to the mighty armies of the Greco-Roman empires and the gymnasiums of modern American high schools. Calisthenics, as opposed to strength training, which uses weights, machines, or resistance bands, uses only the body\'s weight for physical development. The basic form—running, jumping, lifting, stretching, breathing deeply—is as much a part of human existence as eating or sleeping. All that is required for success in calisthenics is time, effort, and dedication; no expensive equipment or special training is needed. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B) Calisthenics first appears around 480 B.C., with Herodotus\' account of the Battle of Thermopolylae. According to Herodotus, before the battle, the god-king Xerxes dispatched a scouting party to spy on his Spartan adversaries. The scouts informed Xerxes that the Spartans, led by King Leonidas, were performing some strange, synchronized movements resembling a tribal dance. Xerxes was delighted. His army numbered over 120,000 men, while the Spartans had only 300. He ordered them all to perform the strange, new-fangled exercise routine. To Xerxes\' astonishment, he discovered that it was not just the Spartans who could perform this unique, choreographed display but his entire army. The Persians won the day. Leonidas was told he had to retreat or face annihilation. On the other hand, the Spartans did not retreat, and in the ensuing battle, they managed to hold Xerxes\' massive army at bay for some time until reinforcements arrived. It turns out that their tribal dance was not a superstitious ritual but rather a form of calisthenics through which they developed incredible physical strength and endurance. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C) Calisthenics was taken seriously by the Greeks not only as a form of military discipline and strength but also as an artistic expression of movement and an aesthetically ideal physique. The term calisthenics derives from the Greek words for beauty and strength. According to historical records and images from period pottery, mosaics, and sculptures, the ancient Olympians took calisthenics training seriously. They were and continue to be admired for their athleticism and physical beauty. In particular, they are remembered for their athletic achievements in chariot racing, wrestling, boxing, discus throwing, javelin, and running. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">D) Calisthenics had a second golden age in the 1800s. Gymnastics, an organized sport that uses bars, rings, vaulting horses, and balancing beams to demonstrate physical prowess, was born in the twentieth century. It evolved from gymnastic exercises performed for practical reasons: to prepare oneself for war, to improve one\'s health, or to develop an aesthetic physique. As such, gymnasts trained in calisthenics became known as \"calists.\" This was also the time when the phenomenon of strongmen emerged. These people of incredible physical strength and development forged nomadic careers by performing incredible feats in front of stunned audiences. </p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">E) Angelo Siciliano, also known as Charles Atlas, was crowned \"The World\'s Most Perfectly Developed Man\" in the 1950s. He advertised the benefits of his muscle toning system, which consisted of simple bodyweight exercises. Atlas\' approach was based on traditional calisthenics, and he taught these methods to hundreds of thousands of children and young adults through a series of mail-order comic books in the 1960s and 1970s. On the other hand, Atlas was the last of a dying breed. The tides were changing, fitness methods were shifting away from calisthenics, and no well-known proponent of the method could ever replace him. </p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">F) Calisthenics and the goal of functional strength combined with physical beauty were replaced in the 1960s and 1970s by emphasizing massive muscles at any cost. This evolved into the sport of bodybuilding. Although the pioneers of bodybuilding were drawn from the calisthenics tradition, the sole goal quickly became an increase in muscle size. A typical workout involved heavy weights, long sets, and little rest between repetitions. Bodybuilders frequently turn to steroids to achieve their goals. This level of physical development was only possible with the use of anabolic steroids, which were synthetic hormones that boosted muscle development while harming overall health. These bodybuilders also used free weights and machines to target and bloat the size of individual muscles rather than developing a naturally proportioned body. With its emphasis on physical beauty and proportional balance, Calisthenics had little to offer the masses of monsters. </p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">G) Calisthenics was restricted to populations thought to be weak, such as women, those recovering from injuries, and schoolchildren in this \"bigger is better\" era. The new emphasis on muscularity did not leave room for the artistry and beauty of the classical forms. It also distinguished calisthenics from weightlifting, gymnastics, and other sports requiring specialized equipment. Although some of the strongest and most physically developed human beings ever to have acquired their abilities through sophisticated calisthenics, a great deal of this knowledge was discarded, and the method was reduced to more than an easily accessible and readily available activity. Those who learned the foundational calisthenics techniques might anticipate moving on to weight training rather than more complex calisthenics.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"> H) However, in recent years, calisthenics has come back into vogue as a fitness trend. Excessive muscle development during bodybuilding is commonly associated with joint pain, injuries, imbalanced physiques, and poor cardiovascular health. Additionally, many people find that the heavy lifting and high volumes of reps used in traditional bodybuilding workouts make it difficult to engage the mind and maintain a positive attitude toward one\'s training. As a result, several of the most recent and well-liked gyms and programs emphasize calisthenics-based techniques. Numerous allied traditions, including yoga, Pilates, kettlebell training, gymnastics, and classical Greco-Roman calisthenics, are frequently incorporated into contemporary practices. Many individuals want to reclaim the ancient Greek understanding of physical excellence, physical sturdiness, and the harmony of the mind-body link.</p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><strong>The text has eight paragraphs, A–H.</strong></p><p><br></p><p> <strong>For questions 21 – 30, choose options (A, B, C, D, E, F, G, or H). Which paragraph contains the following information?</strong></p>', 1144),
