(147, NULL, '<p>Calisthenics</p><p> The oldest form of resistance training </p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A) Calisthenics has endured and thrived because of its simplicity and utility, from the first caveman to scale a tree or hang from a cliff face to the mighty armies of the Greco-Roman empires and the gymnasiums of modern American high schools. Calisthenics, as opposed to strength training, which uses weights, machines, or resistance bands, uses only the body\'s weight for physical development. The basic form—running, jumping, lifting, stretching, breathing deeply—is as much a part of human existence as eating or sleeping. All that is required for success in calisthenics is time, effort, and dedication; no expensive equipment or special training is needed. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B) Calisthenics first appears around 480 B.C., with Herodotus\' account of the Battle of Thermopolylae. According to Herodotus, before the battle, the god-king Xerxes dispatched a scouting party to spy on his Spartan adversaries. The scouts informed Xerxes that the Spartans, led by King Leonidas, were performing some strange, synchronized movements resembling a tribal dance. Xerxes was delighted. His army numbered over 120,000 men, while the Spartans had only 300. He ordered them all to perform the strange, new-fangled exercise routine. To Xerxes\' astonishment, he discovered that it was not just the Spartans who could perform this unique, choreographed display but his entire army. The Persians won the day. Leonidas was told he had to retreat or face annihilation. On the other hand, the Spartans did not retreat, and in the ensuing battle, they managed to hold Xerxes\' massive army at bay for some time until reinforcements arrived. It turns out that their tribal dance was not a superstitious ritual but rather a form of calisthenics through which they developed incredible physical strength and endurance. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">C) Calisthenics was taken seriously by the Greeks not only as a form of military discipline and strength but also as an artistic expression of movement and an aesthetically ideal physique. The term calisthenics derives from the Greek words for beauty and strength. According to historical records and images from period pottery, mosaics, and sculptures, the ancient Olympians took calisthenics training seriously. They were and continue to be admired for their athleticism and physical beauty. In particular, they are remembered for their athletic achievements in chariot racing, wrestling, boxing, discus throwing, javelin, and running. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">D) Calisthenics had a second golden age in the 1800s. Gymnastics, an organized sport that uses bars, rings, vaulting horses, and balancing beams to demonstrate physical prowess, was born in the twentieth century. It evolved from gymnastic exercises performed for practical reasons: to prepare oneself for war, to improve one\'s health, or to develop an aesthetic physique. As such, gymnasts trained in calisthenics became known as \"calists.\" This was also the time when the phenomenon of strongmen emerged. These people of incredible physical strength and development forged nomadic careers by performing incredible feats in front of stunned audiences. </p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">E) Angelo Siciliano, also known as Charles Atlas, was crowned \"The World\'s Most Perfectly Developed Man\" in the 1950s. He advertised the benefits of his muscle toning system, which consisted of simple bodyweight exercises. Atlas\' approach was based on traditional calisthenics, and he taught these methods to hundreds of thousands of children and young adults through a series of mail-order comic b