ty rather than psychically moving across an area.<br><br><strong>Extract B</strong><br>Immersion is the sensation of being completely involved in a virtual environment. In contrast to monitor experiences, which we only see via a more-or-less distant window, things appear to be happening around us in VR. They appear near and immediate, even lifelike, especially when your entire body is participating in the connection. When you meet someone in Virtual Reality, you have the sensation that you are actually face-to-face talking to them.<br>The greater the immersion impact and the better the technology employed, the more imaginative the developed world will be. High-resolution screens with stereoscopic picture reproduction and fast frame rates attempt to make the depiction as accurate as feasible.<br><strong><br>Extract C</strong><br>Almost every mainstream VR headsets come with their own VR controllers that are tailored to the tracking technology. They imitate finger, arm, and hand movements and let users to engage with Virtual Reality by pressing a button or using analogue sticks or touchpads.<br>You may hold a controller in each hand at times to control various components of the experience. In certain circumstances, the controllers provide virtual depiction of your hands that allows you to orchestrate the environment and items inside it in ways similar to how you might in real life.<br><br><strong>Extract D</strong><br>However, in the future, VR control might go much further. VR attachments will allow you to control VR games with brain impulses. Many VR companies are researching brain-computer interfaces for gaming and VR. They believe that in the future, we will be able to influence our brains via external stimuli.<br>Mind control will be included into future VR and AR systems, according to many VR creators. The future of VR is set to bring input devices that use haptic feedback to attain a better level of immersion. Physical feedback will be sent to the user in the form of impulses or vibrations. You will be able to sense what\'s going on in the virtual environment, detect resistance, and even be able to feel the textures of items.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><br></span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span lang=\"EN\" style=\"line-height: 115%; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 18px;\">For questions <strong>21 – 30</strong>, choose options (<strong>A, B, C, or D</strong>). Which do you think answers the questions? </span></span><br></p>', 1391),
