t-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Sir Isaac Newton and Christiaan Huygens offered two hypotheses describing the behavior of light back in the 1600s. The former put up a particle or \"</span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">corpuscular</span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">\" </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">hypothesis</span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">, whilst the latter offered a wave theory. Huygen\'s method had significant flaws and did not match the observation, but Newton was given full backing due to his name. So, Newton\'s hypothesis </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">predominated </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">for more than a century.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">The corpuscular idea encountered significant difficulties in the early 1900s. Diffraction had been seen by scientists, but it had been difficult to fully explain. The apparent wave behavior was shown in Thomas Young\'s well-known double-slit experiment. Additionally, it supported the wave theory of Huygens over Newton\'s particle theory.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">It is thought that waves move via a medium of some kind. Huygen suggested medium was luminiferous aether or ether in current </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">terminology</span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">. When James Maxwell quantified a set of equations, this was further explained. These equations provided a </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">wave-propagation</span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\"> explanation for electromagnetic radiation and visible light. The experimental results confirmed his </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">predictions </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">as being largely consistent, and he made the assumption that ether served as the transmission medium.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">The lack of ether was the main issue with the wave hypothesis. James Bradley\'s stellar aberration investigations from 1720 revealed that ether needed to remain </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">motionless </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">in relation to Earth\'s motion. Many researchers during the 1900s tried to detect either or its motion directly. One such experiment was the Michelson-Morley experiment. Unfortunately, ether was not found in any of the studies. These unsuccessful attempts marked the start of a heated argument over whether light is a wave or a particle.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">In his article from 1905, Einstein described the photoelectric effect. According to the article, light moves as a distinct bundle of energy. A photon is a particle with energy that has a relationship to light frequency. After the term \"photon\" was first used, this </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">hypothesis </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">became known as the \"photon theory” in later years.\" Etheric propagation was no longer necessary with the discovery of photons. The puzzling contradiction of why wave behavior was seen, however, remained unsolved. The Compton effect and the double-slit experiment\'s quantum variations were even stranger quantum variations, supporting the particle </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">interpretation</span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">After experiments were conducted and evidence gathered, the following conclusions were alarming:</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">“Light functions as both a wave and particle. Its nature depends on the circumstances of an experiment and the time of observations.”</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Now the next question was: Does such duality exist in matter as well? The de Broglie hypothesis, an expansion of Einstein\'s work to link the matter\'s wavelength to its </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">momentum</span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">, provided the solution. Successful investigations in 1927 verified the hypothesis, and de Broglie was awarded the Nobel Prize for his contributions.</span></p><br><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">It has been discovered that matter, like light, may display both wave and particle qualities depending on the circumstances. Massive objects have shorter wavelengths that are trivially tiny when thought of as waves. However, as demonstrated by the </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">double-slit</span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\"> experiment with electrons, wavelengths may be seen for smaller objects and are often greater.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Through a differential equation, wave-particle duality describes the physical behavior of light and matter. The </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Schrodinger </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">equation is used to represent a wave function in this equation. Simply said, the essence of quantum physics is the capacity to represent reality as waves.</span></p><br></strong></p><p></p>', 1428),
