-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Floods have an evident negative impact on the environment, </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:#ffff00;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">(20….?)</span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">. </span><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Rapid flood waters spend little time in a purifying environment (such as the ground or a wetland), preventing the surface flow from losing the soil particle contaminants it has accumulated. Streambanks and the soil\'s surface are also eroded by their pace. Additionally, tree roots might be drowned in new areas of standing water.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.2;text-align: justify;margin-top:6pt;margin-bottom:6pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Answer the following questions:&nbsp;</span></p></strong><br class=\"Apple-interchange-newline\"><b style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-85dc5e8b-7fff-313a-c35f-5ebb6409c5dd\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Instructions: Five sentences have been removed from the text. Choose from the sentences (A – G) the one which fits each gap (15 – 20). There is one extra sentence that you do not need to use.</span></b></p>', 1440),
(346, NULL, '<p><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-2a09ce1e-7fff-9652-2284-b0f739d14f17\"><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.7999999999999998;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Read the Four extracts below on the theme of Types of Galaxies:</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.7999999999999998;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">For questions 21 – 30, choose options (A, B, C, or D). Which do you think answers the questions?&nbsp;</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.7999999999999998;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:italic;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Which Extract…</span></p></strong><br class=\"Apple-interchange-newline\"><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-d3108e49-7fff-d2a8-8cc8-60224a9c2727\"><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Extract A</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">The idea of galaxies is both exciting and perplexing. You get a brain freeze when you consider that the Milky Way, our galaxy, has over 100 billion planets and that Earth is but a little speck in the cosmos. We get increasingly intrigued by the universe\'s mystery as we give it more thought.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Galaxies contain up to a million or a trillion stars and are vast systems of gas, dark matter, and primarily dust. It\'s all kept together by gravity, and it\'s thought that the cores of nearly all bigger galaxies are home to supermassive black holes. The sun is just one of the 100 to 400 billion stars that make up Sagittarius A*, a supermassive black hole in the Milky Way that has a mass comparable to around four million suns.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">There are many galaxies in the universe that have not yet been found. Since the Hubble telescope has seen up to 100 billion galaxies, scientists estimate that there may be up to 200 billion galaxies in the universe.</span></p></strong></p><p><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-d3108e49-7fff-d2a8-8cc8-60224a9c2727\"><br></strong></p><p><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-d3108e49-7fff-d2a8-8cc8-60224a9c2727\"><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-ffd88c1f-7fff-03af-e6c4-c5f178cd8156\"><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Extract B</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">According to astronomers, 180 million years after the big bang, the universe\'s earliest stars are thought to have ignited. The beginning of the universe as we know it now may be traced back to the big bang, which took place 13.8 billion years ago. When the universe rotated about 400 million years ago, or less than 3% of its present age, gravity shaped the early galaxies into their current shape.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">With a few exceptions, research says that almost all galaxies are surrounded by huge haloes of dark matter. Theoretically, astronomers think that the massive tendrils of dark matter gave the matter the gravitational framework necessary for it to coalesce into the first galaxies in the early universe. The Milky Way was the only galaxy humans were aware of before the 20th century. Because of their fuzziness and cloud-like appearance, astronomers used to refer to neighbouring galaxies as \"nebulae.\"</span></p></strong></strong></p><p><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-d3108e49-7fff-d2a8-8cc8-60224a9c2727\"><br></strong></p><p><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-d3108e49-7fff-d2a8-8cc8-60224a9c2727\"><br></strong></p><p><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-d3108e49-7fff-d2a8-8cc8-60224a9c2727\"><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6adf3b3f-7fff-356b-9e92-142c345fb5ae\"><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Extract C</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Even though Andromeda is the nearest and greatest galaxy to the Milky Way, it is still more than 2.5 million years away. It is fascinating that even though it is thousands of light-years away, it is still brilliant enough to be seen with the unaided eye in the Northern Hemisphere.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">&nbsp;</span><br></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">All known galaxies, more than two-thirds, are spirals. This galaxy features a flat rotating disc and a spiral arm-adorned centre bulge. The matter in the disc may take on the appearance of a cosmic spin wheel and take on a characteristic spiral form as they spin at speeds of hundreds of kilometres per second. A straight, starry bar runs through the centre of the Milky Way.</span></p><br></strong><b style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-2203034a-7fff-5f05-36b7-99b727b6e83c\"><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Extract D</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">One of the lenticular galaxies is the Sombrero Galaxy. This kind of galaxy falls midway between spiral and elliptical galaxies. Because they resemble lenses, they are referred to be lenticular. They have a narrow disc of rotating stars and a centre bulge. They lack spiral arms, in contrast to spiral galaxies. They include some dust and interstellar material. They generally arise in areas of space that are intensively occupied.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Elliptical galaxies are spherical, as their name implies, but they can also stretch along a single axis. The elongation is so great that they resemble a cigar. The biggest known galaxies in the cosmos are elliptical galaxies, which have the capacity to hold more than a trillion stars. The distance between the stars in the galaxy might be above two million light-years. Dwarf elliptical galaxies are elliptical galaxies that are smaller than normal elliptical galaxies. Elliptical galaxies only have a little chance of producing brand-new stars, but they do have interstellar matter, older stars, and some dust. Like the discs of spiral galaxies, the stars orbit the galactic centre in a random manner.</span></p><br></b></strong></p>', 1441);
