n with the unaided eye in the Northern Hemisphere.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">&nbsp;</span><br></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">All known galaxies, more than two-thirds, are spirals. This galaxy features a flat rotating disc and a spiral arm-adorned centre bulge. The matter in the disc may take on the appearance of a cosmic spin wheel and take on a characteristic spiral form as they spin at speeds of hundreds of kilometres per second. A straight, starry bar runs through the centre of the Milky Way.</span></p><br></strong><b style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-2203034a-7fff-5f05-36b7-99b727b6e83c\"><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Extract D</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">One of the lenticular galaxies is the Sombrero Galaxy. This kind of galaxy falls midway between spiral and elliptical galaxies. Because they resemble lenses, they are referred to be lenticular. They have a narrow disc of rotating stars and a centre bulge. They lack spiral arms, in contrast to spiral galaxies. They include some dust and interstellar material. They generally arise in areas of space that are intensively occupied.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Elliptical galaxies are spherical, as their name implies, but they can also stretch along a single axis. The elongation is so great that they resemble a cigar. The biggest known galaxies in the cosmos are elliptical galaxies, which have the capacity to hold more than a trillion stars. The distance between the stars in the galaxy might be above two million light-years. Dwarf elliptical galaxies are elliptical galaxies that are smaller than normal elliptical galaxies. Elliptical galaxies only have a little chance of producing brand-new stars, but they do have interstellar matter, older stars, and some dust. Like the discs of spiral galaxies, the stars orbit the galactic centre in a random manner.</span></p><br></b></strong></p>', 1442),
