 billion galaxies, scientists estimate that there may be up to 200 billion galaxies in the universe.</span></p></strong></p><p><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-d3108e49-7fff-d2a8-8cc8-60224a9c2727\"><br></strong></p><p><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-d3108e49-7fff-d2a8-8cc8-60224a9c2727\"><strong style=\"font-weight:normal;\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-ffd88c1f-7fff-03af-e6c4-c5f178cd8156\"><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:700;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">Extract B</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;\">According to astronomers, 180 million years after the big bang, the universe\'s earliest stars are thought to have ignited. The beginning of the universe as we know it now may be traced back to the big bang, which took place 13.8 billion years ago. When the universe rotated about 400 million years ago, or less than 3% of its present age, gravity shaped the early galaxies into their current shape.</span></p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.3800000000000001;text-align: justify;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:\'Times New Roman\',serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space