(1124, 'What is the central idea behind the passage?', 'Concerning spot-fixing in cricket matches and the inability of top cricketers to speak out.', 'A press conference regarding the cricket match.', 'BCCI held a press conference.', 'A press conference with cricketers.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A', 'In the passage it clearly states that the writer believes that the best cricketers need to address the media at a news conference to reassure those who watch sports about its positive aspects.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1125, 'What situation is this passage referring to?', 'In this scenario, cricketers dispute with BCCI.', 'A scenario in which cricketers speak to the media to calm their fears regarding spot fixation in cricket.', 'In this scenario, cricketers discuss the vice president and the president.', 'A scenario in which the BCCI hosts an event to calm the fears of cricket fans of spot-fixing in cricket.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The author believes that if the best cricketers spoke up, the cricket-loving public would be convinced about the sport\'s future.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1126, 'The passage states that there are specific conditions under which cricketers are allowed to speak. What are these requirements?', 'If the congressman let them speak, they could.', 'If the BCCI gives players the right to speak, the BCCI will pay them.', 'If they show their character strength and let go of their selfish goals.', 'If the reporter decides to withdraw his report.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'C', 'The critic believes that if professional cricketers show strength of character, they would disregard the threats and speak up.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1127, 'The passage mentions that ‘their press conference together will be just as hollow as the one from the cricket administrators’ What is this referring to?', 'The cricketers’ skulls have no brains.', 'The brains of administrators are hollow.', 'The vice president and presidents are hollow', 'The critic believes that cricketers lack the quality of their character.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'D', '. The critic believes that because the cricket players lack strength of character and live in constant fear of those who manage the sport, they are unable to talk freely and honestly, and even if they did, their remarks would be just as empty as those of the controllers.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1128, 'What situation has the reporter uncovered?', 'He would like congressmen to take part in the press conference.', 'The top cricketers should get away from the sport of cricket.', 'He is requesting BCCI to speak at an event in the press to dispel the concerns of the public that the sport is not fair.', 'The cricketers are asked to speak at an event in the press to dispel the public\'s concerns that the game is corrupt.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'D', 'The writer thinks that the best cricketers are hesitant to discuss the topic as much as he would like them to.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1129, 'In the passage, the word \"platitudes\" is mentioned. What is it?', 'A flattering comment.', 'A positive comment.', 'A common, insipid expression.', 'A harsh comment.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'C', 'The critic claims that even if the best cricketers held a news conference, they would simply say a few broad, superficial statements. Platitude is a word for meaningless speech.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1130, 'What might be the reason for writing this poem?', 'Patriotism was the reason that drove the poet to pen this poem.', 'Poet had a dream of getting the Nobel Prize.', 'The publisher wanted the poet to write the poem.', 'The British made poet write this poem.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The poem was written during a time when the British were oppressing minorities. The poet wished that a minority group would be freed from British rule. According to the poet, minorities would do far better if they handled their own affairs', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1131, 'What kind of poem is \'Where the Mind is in Peace’?', 'Epic', 'Ballad', 'Limerick', 'Free Verse', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The poem is free verse, therefore it lacks rhymes and metrical structures. Epic poetry is longer, more in-depth, and more narrative in nature. A ballad is a type of narrative that is also told musically. A limerick is a five-line rhyming poetry that is frequently amusing or satirical with lines 1, 2, and 5 rhyme, while lines 3 and 4 also rhyme but have different sounds.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1132, 'Which of the following are metaphors?', '\"The mind is free of anxiety.\"', '\" Where the unmistakable stream of logic.\"', '\" When knowledge is free.\"', '\" The constant striving of its arms.\"', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The comparison between reason and an unmistakable stream is metaphorical. A metaphor is a separate figure of speech in which you express something using entirely different terms than what is required.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1133, 'What expression is \" The constant striving of its arms in the direction of the goal of perfection.\"?', 'Irony in the situation', 'Idiom', 'Personification', 'Euphemism', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '. Personification is the process of giving a non-human idea or concept a human characteristic or capacity. A personification in the poem is \"The constant striving of its arms in the direction of the goal of perfection.\" Here, the idea of \"constant striving\" has taken the form of a person reaching out in pursuit of perfection.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1134, 'Which among the following is not an alliteration?', '\"head is high.\"', '\"Where the world.\"', '\"To the dull desert sands of dead habits.\"', '\"By the narrow walls of domestic.\"', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Alliteration is the practice of beginning each word in a line of verse with the same consonant sound repeatedly. The first three options are all alliteration while the four words in \'By the narrow walls of domestic\' have different consonant sounds', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1135, 'What do lines 7, \" Where the unmistakable stream of logic has not lost its direction” and 8, \" To the desert sands of dead habits,\" refer to?', 'Poet would like the ability to reason given to his fellow citizens to allow them to evict the old customs and practices.', 'Poet was adamant that national highways should be constructed.', 'Poet had a dream to link all the rivers that flow through India.', 'Poet was adamant about making the world more welcoming.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Minority people were entangled in a variety of mindlessly followed customs and traditions. The poet wished to endow them with the capacity to reason so they might examine the customs objectively and get rid of old habits. The poet use metaphors as literary devices to emphasize their point of view.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1136, 'What kind of phrase is \" To the dull desert sands of dead habits\"?', 'Idiom', 'Personification', 'Metaphor', 'Verbal irony', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'This metaphor compares a dead habit to the dull desert sand. A metaphor is a figure of speech in which you describe something using entirely unrelated terms to those that are necessary.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1137, 'What is the meaning of Line 3 of the poem \" The world hasn\'t been broken into fragments” and Line 4 of the poem \" By the narrow walls of domestic\" refers to?', 'The country shouldn\'t split into administrative subdivisions.', 'Poet is a fan of a nation that is not divided due to prejudices based on creed, caste color, religion, or any other unjustified superstitions in the country.', 'The country shouldn\'t be divided based on the rivers that flow within the country.', 'The nation should not be divided into sub-divisions according to lifestyles in food', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'According to the poet, the British were attempting to implement a divide and rule strategy based on the internal prejudices of minorities related to caste, creed, religion, and superstitions. The poet believed that under their own government, minorities would be better off since all needless domestic walls would fall down, allowing them to live in peace with total freedom of action and self-rule.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1138, 'What is the meaning of the line, “I pray to my Father that my country wakes up in that eternal paradise of freedom.” What do you think it means?', 'It was evident that the minority was lazy and must be made active.', 'The minority was always sleeping, and the poet was begging them to awaken', 'That minority was lying and wanted to speak the truth.', 'That minority should be free from British rule and countless domestic social problems.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The poet was obviously concerned by how the British tyranny of the minority was exacerbated by the inconsistencies within the minority, which were exemplified by its superstitions and the extreme diversity of its culture, color, language, and religion. The poet wished for the freedom of the minority from both British Rule and these differences.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1139, 'What emotion does the poem communicate?', 'It reveals that minorities are being repressed through oppression by British rule. Poet is adamant about being free.', 'It conveys the idea that minorities tend to be cowards.', 'It signals the idea that minorities are trapped in their culture.', 'It communicates the idea that a minority is ravaged by conflict.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The poet uses the \'opposite\' form to depict the plight of the minority under British Rule during the time the poem was written, while it was under British rule. For instance, the phrase \"head high\" actually means \"head bowed down,\" which indicates that minority were not treated with dignity.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
