(1152, 'body building’s pioneers\' sole goal became an increase in muscle size.', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F', 'G', 'H', 'F', '- body building’s pioneers were drawn from the calisthenics tradition; the sole goal soon became an increase in muscle size.', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1153, 'tribal dance is a form of calisthenics', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F', 'G', 'H', 'B', '- It turns out their tribal dance was not a superstitious ritual but a form of calisthenics', 83, NULL, 0, 1),
(1154, 'Winston was given 100 pencils, out of which 30% were blue. The teacher asked him to distribute 15% of the blue pencils to his classmates. How many blue pencils did Winston distribute?', '5', '6', '4', '3', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '30% of 100 pencils are 30, which represent the blue ones. 15% of 30 is 4.5, but since we can\'t have half a pencil, we have 4 blue pencils distributed by Winston.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1155, 'James is planning to grow apples in his home garden and save on his monthly grocery bill. Given that he usually spends $75 on apples each month and he expects a 20% decrease in the monthly apple expense due to his new garden, how much will he spend on apples each month once the garden is fully functional?', '$50', '$60', '$63', '$55', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', '20% decrease from $75 will be $15. As $75-$15 equals to $60, James can expect to spend $60 on apples each month.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1156, 'Nathan used 60% of his salary to pay for his house down payment. If his salary is $5000, how much did he use for the house down payment?', '$2000', '$2500', '$3000', '$3500', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The amount used for the house down payment is 60% of $5000, which gives us $3000.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1157, 'Carl wanted to buy a ship model that had a discount of 30% on the original price of $500. How much did Carl pay for the ship model?', '$350', '$370', '$400', '$450', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '30% off on an item of $500 is $150, so Carl only had to pay $350 for the ship model.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1158, 'Zoya owns a business that produced a profit of $10,000 this year. If the business makes a profit 20% less than this year\'s profit next year, how much profit will the business make next year?', '$8000', '$8200', '$9000', '$7500', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '20% less of the $10,000 profit Zoya should expect is $2,000. Therefore, the profit should be $10,000 - $2,000 = $8,000.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1159, 'Oliver books increased in price by 15% on a price of $50. What was the new price of the book?', '$55', '$57.5', '$60', '$65', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'A 15% increase on $50 is $7.5, hence the new price of the book was $50 + $7.5 = $57.5.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1160, 'Daisy started a small bakery shop and was making some chocolate cakes. If she managed to sell 25% more cakes in February than in January where she sold 120 cakes, how many cakes did she sell in February?', '140', '150', '160', '145', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', '25% of 120 cakes equal 30 cakes. Therefore, in February she managed to sell 120 cakes + 30 cakes, which equals 150 cakes.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1161, 'Clara is a pizza shop owner. She usually sells 400 pizzas a week. This week, she observed a 25% increase in sales. How many pizzas did she sell this week?', '450', '475', '500', '525', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', '25% increase from 400 pizzas will be 100. So Clara sold 400+100 = 500 pizzas this week.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1162, 'Emma and Lucy decided to split their monthly rent of their apartment, which cost $600. If Lucy paid 60% of the rent, how much did Emma pay?', '$240', '$300', '$360', '$280', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'If Lucy paid 60%, Emma paid the remaining 40%. Therefore, Emma paid 40% of $600, which is $240.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1163, 'John wanted to buy a car worth $25,000. However, he only had 80% of the amount. How much more money did John need to buy the car?', '$1000', '$2000', '$3000', '$5000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'If John had 80% of the price, he was missing 20%. 20% of $25,000 equals $5,000, which is the amount needed to reach the full price.', 84, NULL, 0, 1),
(1175, 'Alice wants to buy a chocolate cake or a carrot cake for a party. If there are 7 chocolate cakes and 5 carrot cakes in the bakery and Alice randomly selects a cake, what is the probability she selects a carrot cake?', '35%', '40%', '42%', '47%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'There are total of 12 cakes in the bakery and 5 out of those 12 cakes are carrot cakes, so the probability is 5/12 = 0.42 or 42%.', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1176, 'John runs a large apple business, and his warehouse holds exactly 1,000 containers, each filled with either red or green apples. The chance that any given container holds red apples is 35%. If John randomly selects a container, what is the probability that it holds green apples?', '35%', '65%', '45%', '55%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Given that the total sum of probabilities in any situation equals 1, the probability of the selected apple basket being green is just 1 minus the probability of it being red, which is 1 - 0.35 = 0.65 or 65%.', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1177, 'Emma receives books for her birthday. There\'s a 60% chance a book is a romance novel and a 40% chance it\'s a mystery. What\'s the probability that the next book she unwraps will be a romance novel?', '10%', '30%', '50%', '60%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The probability it\'s a romance novel is given outright: it\'s 60%. There is no additional information or unnecessary confusion.', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1178, 'There is a 55% chance that it will rain in the evening. Therefore, Zoya decides whether to take an umbrella to her business meeting. If it does not rain, then taking an umbrella was unnecessary. What is the probability that Zoya took an umbrella unnecessarily?', '25%', '35%', '45%', '55%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'If there is a 55% chance it will rain, that means there is a 45% chance it will not rain. Thus, if Zoya takes an umbrella, there\'s a 45% chance she did so unnecessarily.', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1179, 'An apartment house contains 2 men for every 3 women. If a person is chosen at random, what is the probability he or she is a man?', '0.4', '0.5', '0.6', '0.67', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'There are 2 men and (2+3) = 5 total people in the building. The probability the person is a man is 2/5 = 0.4.', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1180, 'Clive noticed that at a train station 3 out of 5 trains leaving there are cargo trains. If Clive randomly sees a train depart, what is the probability that it\'s a cargo train?', '40%', '50%', '60%', '80%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Out of every 5 trains, 3 are cargo trains. This means that the probability of a randomly selected train being a cargo train is 3/5 = 0.6 or 60%', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1181, 'Luke runs a bee farm and produces honey. The chance that a jar of honey contains a honeycomb piece is 15%. If Luke selects 5 jars randomly, what is the probability that at least one of the selected jars contains a honeycomb piece?', '50%', '21%', '36%', '55%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The probability that a jar does not contain a honeycomb piece is 85%. The probability none of the jars among the 5 selected contain a honeycomb piece is 0.85^5 = 0.4437. Thus the probability that at least one jar contains a honeycomb piece is 1 - 0.4437 = 0.5562 ~ 56%', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1182, 'A ship carrying 100 pencils and 300 pens capsizes. If a stationary observer at a fixed point on the shore randomly picks a pencil or pen washed ashore, what\'s the probability that it is a pencil?', '25%', '75%', '33%', '66%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total number of pencils and pens is 400, and there are 100 pencils, so the probability is 100/400, which is 25%.', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1183, 'Henry has a jar of 5 green and 3 red apples. He picks two apples at random. What\'s the probability of picking two green apples?', '5/14', '3/14', '10/14', '1/14', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'There are total of 8 apples out of which 5 are green. The probability of first picking a green apple is 5/8. After removing one green apple, the probability for second is 4/7. So, to find the probability of both events happening, multiply them: (5/8) x (4/7) = 20/56 = 5/14.', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1184, 'Nathan and Lucy are making pizzas for a park gathering. If they make 4 cheese, 8 pepperoni, and 2 veggie pizzas, and Nathan, without looking, picks one up to put in the oven, what is the probability that he picks up a veggie pizza?', '1/7', '2/7', '3/7', '4/7', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total amount of pizzas made is 14, and there are only 2 veggie pizzas, so the probability is 2/14, which is 1/7.', 86, NULL, 0, 1),
(1185, 'Diana is a teacher. She gives her students 2 pencils each for the entire course. If there are 3/5 of the total students left in her class, and there were 50 students initially, how many pencils does she need to give?', '70 pencils', '60 pencils', '55 pencils', '65 pencils', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Initially total students were 50. 3/5 are left, which would be 50*3/5 = 30. Each student needs 2 pencils. So, she would need 30*2 = 60 pencils.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1186, 'Charlie is a chef. He uses 1/4 of a jar of honey for each pizza he makes. If he has 12 jars of honey, how many pizzas can he make?', '32 pizzas', '45 pizzas', '48 pizzas', '35 pizzas', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'One jar of honey makes 4 pizzas. So, 12 jars will make 12*4 = 48 pizzas.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1187, 'Lucy owns an apparel business and decides to reward her employees by distributing jackets. If she buys 50 jackets and gives each employee 2/5 of a jacket, how many employees can she reward?', '75 employees', '100 employees', '125 employees', '150 employees', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'A single jacket can be distributed among 5 employees (1/0.2). Therefore, 50 jackets can be distributed among 5*50 = 250 employees.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1188, 'Mary baked a cake and cut it into 5 pieces. She ate 2/5 of it for dinner. How many pieces are left?', '2 pieces', '3 pieces', '4 pieces', '1 piece', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Mary ate 2/5*5 = 2 pieces. Therefore, 5 - 2 = 3 pieces are left.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1189, 'Shane, an automaker, spends 1/2 of his salary on parts for his car. If his salary is $1000, how much does he spend on parts?', '$400', '$200', '$500', '$600', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Shane spends $1000*1/2 = $500 on parts.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1190, 'Henry bought 8 apples. He ate 3/8 of the apples in the morning before going to work in his office. How many apples did he eat?', '2 apples', '4 apples', '3 apples', '5 apples', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Multiply 8 by 3/8 = 1*3 = 3. So, Henry ate 3 apples.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1191, 'Georgia, a college student, spends 3/4 of her day studying. If she has 24 hours in a day, how many hours does she spend studying?', '12 hours', '16 hours', '18 hours', '20 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Georgia spends 24*3/4 = 18 hours studying.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1192, 'Carl, a mathematics teacher shared 1/5 of his 25 books with his students. How many books did he share?', '4 books', '5 books', '6 books', '7 books', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Carl shared 25*1/5 = 5 books.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1193, 'Peter bought 20 glasses for his newly opened restaurant. Unfortunately, 1/4 of them broke while being shipped. How many glasses does he have left?', '18 glasses', '16 glasses', '15 glasses', '14 glasses', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '1/4*20 = 5 glasses broke. Therefore, 20 - 5 = 15 glasses are left.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1194, 'Marcus launched 10 rockets in a park, but 2/10 failed to reach the sky. How many rockets were successful?', '7 rockets', '9 rockets', '8 rockets', '6 rockets', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '2/10*10 = 2 rockets failed. Therefore, 10 - 2 = 8 rockets were successful.', 87, NULL, 0, 1),
(1195, 'James is a train driver who drives at a speed of 90 mph. If he has to cover a distance of 360 miles, considering he makes a stop of 15 minutes after every 90 minutes, how long will it take him to reach his destination?', '4 hours', '4.5 hours', '5 hours', '3.75 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'First, calculate travel time without any stops, which is distance/speed = 360/90 = 4 hours. Then, consider that James stops every 90 minutes. Therefore, for each \'chunk\' of travel of 1.5 hours, there is an added 15 minutes break. The total driving time is 4 hours = 240 minutes. There, he has (240/90)*15 = 40 minutes\' worth of breaks. Total travel time = 240 + 40 = 280 minutes = 5 hours.', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
(1196, 'Eliza is a baker who is preparing to make her famous apple cakes for a big event. She has 80 apples, and each cake requires 4 apples. If she makes an error and uses 5 apples for the first cake, how many cakes can she make?', '19 cakes', '20 cakes', '18 cakes', '15 cakes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'After making the first cake, Eliza will have 80 - 5 = 75 apples. She can then make 75 ÷ 4 = 18.75 cakes with the remaining apples. Since she cannot make .75 of a cake, she will only manage to make 18 additional full cakes. Therefore, with the first cake, she will make a total of 19 cakes.', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
(1197, 'Emma is dieting and plans to eat 2 slices of pizza for dinner. If one slice of pizza contains 285 calories, how many calories would Emma consume from eating pizza in a week?', '3990 calories', '3000 calories', '4050 calories', '3570 calories', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'First calculate daily calorie intake from pizza: 2 slices * 285 calories per slice = 570 calories per day. Then find the weekly calorie intake: 7 days * 570 calories = 3990 calories.', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
(1198, 'Carl owns a business where he sells jackets and pencils. If he sold 20 sets of jackets and pencils for $60 each, however, needed to refund 2 customers $30 each due to damaged jackets, what was Carl\'s total revenue?', '$1100', '$1180', '$1200', '$1160', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Initially, Carl\'s total sales were:  $ 60 * 20 = $ 1200. But he had to refund two customers: $30 * 2 = $60. Therefore, his final revenue was: $1200 - $60 = $1140', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
(1199, 'Nora is an author who has a deadline to write 200 pages book. If her daily target is to write 10 pages, and one day she writes for 8 hours, how many books will she end up writing in a year?', '45.6 books', '17.4 books', '10.2 books', '18.25 books', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'First, find the total number of pages she writes in a year: 10 pages/day * 365 days/year = 3650 pages. Then, divide the total pages by the number of pages in one book: 3650/200=18.25. So, Nora will be able to write approximately 18 books in a year.', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
(1200, 'Diana is an engineer who works on systems of ships. There are 5 ships, each needing 12 days maintenance once a year. If maintenance is done simultaneously for all ships, how many days are spent on maintenance for one year?', '60 days', '72 days', '66 days', '12 days', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'As all ships are maintained simultaneously, the time spent on maintenance remains 12 days as each ship is maintained in parallel with the others.', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
(1201, 'Alice works in a chocolate boutique and she has a jar of 120 glasses of honey. If one batch of chocolate-covered apples requires 4 glasses of honey, how many batches can she make?', '25 batches', '30 batches', '35 batches', '40 batches', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Dividing the total glasses of honey by the number of glasses per batch gives you the total number of batches Alice can make: 120/4= 30. So the answer is 30 batches.', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
(1202, 'Henry is a business owner who wishes to increase the salary of his 15 men by 15%. If their combined salary is $10000, what will be their combined salary post the hike?', '$10,000', '$11,500', '$10,500', '$11,000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'A 15% increase of the combined salary is calculated by multiplying the total salary by 15/100. We then add this result to the original combined salary to achieve the new total: $10000 + (15/100) x $10000 = $11500, hence option b is the correct answer.', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
(1203, 'Peter is a teacher and notices some of the boys left their jackets in the park. If he found 12 jackets and knows that 1 in 4 boys left their jackets, how many boys were at the park?', '36 boys', '48 boys', '54 boys', '50 boys', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'If 1 in 4 boys left their jacket, and Peter found 12 jackets, that means 4*12=48 boys were at the park.', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
(1204, 'Charlie wants to buy a car costing $25,000. He plans to save $1,000 each month towards buying the car. If he saves consistently every month, how many months will it take Charlie to save enough money to purchase the car?', '20 months', '24 months', '25 months', '30 months', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'To find out how long it will take Charlie to save enough money, we simply need to divide the total cost of the car by his monthly savings: $25,000/$1,000 = 25 months.', 88, NULL, 0, 1),
