(1421, 'Which instance was responsible for causing a debate about whether light is a particle or wave?', 'Michelson-Morley experiment', 'James Bradley\'s investigations', 'Both A & B', 'None of the above', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'James Bradley\'s stellar aberration investigations from 1720 revealed that ether needed to remain motionless in relation to Earth\'s motion. One such experiment was the Michelson-Morley experiment. Unfortunately, ether was not found in any of the studies. These unsuccessful attempts marked the start of a heated argument over whether light is a wave or a particle', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1422, 'Which scientist contributed to the double-slit experiment?', 'Huygen', 'Young', 'Einstein', 'Newton', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The apparent wave behavior was shown in Thomas Young\'s well-known double-slit experiment. Additionally, it supported the wave theory of Huygens over Newton\'s particle theory.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1423, 'Based on the comprehension, how would you define reality?', 'It is what we experience daily', 'It depends on various factors', 'It changes with time', 'It cannot be identified', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Reality is what we make through the things we experience every day.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1424, 'How do we understand the wave-propagation explanation?', 'With the help of James Maxwell’s equations', 'ons B: By Young’s double-slit experiment', 'Through Huygen’s \"corpuscular\" hypothesis', 'Through James Bradley\'s experiments', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Huygen suggested medium was luminiferous aether or ether in current terminology. When James Maxwell quantified a set of equations, this was further explained. These equations provided a wave-propagation explanation for electromagnetic radiation and visible light.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1425, 'Which of the following statements is correct?', 'A: Etheric propagation resulted in the discovery of photons', 'Light is neither wave nor particle', 'Ether does not have to be motionless in relation to Earth\'s motion', 'None of the above', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Etheric propagation was no longer necessary with the discovery of photons. Light functions as both a wave and a particle. ether needed to remain motionless in relation to Earth\'s motion.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1426, 'Which of the following statements is incorrect?', 'Huygen\'s method had significant flaws', 'Newton\'s hypothesis prevailed for more than a century', 'Huygen\'s method did not have any significant flaws', 'Huygen\'s method did not match the observation', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'All statements are true except C because Huygen\'s method had significant flaws and did not match the observation', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1427, 'How did Einstein describe light?', 'Light moves in the form of waves', 'Light moves as a distinct bundle of energy', 'Light moves in the form of particles', 'Light moves with respect to light frequency', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'In his article from 1905, Einstein described the photoelectric effect. According to the article, light moves as a distinct bundle of energy. A photon is a particle with energy that has a relationship to light frequency. After the term \"photon\" was first used.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1428, 'Which of the following statements is factually accurate?', 'Bigger objects have bigger wavelengths', 'Wavelengths for smaller objects are often smaller', 'Bigger objects have shorter wavelengths', 'Quantum physics cannot represent reality as waves', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Massive objects have shorter wavelengths that are trivially tiny when thought of as waves. However, as demonstrated by the double-slit experiment with electrons, wavelengths may be seen for smaller objects and are often greater. the essence of quantum physics is the capacity to represent reality as waves.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1429, 'Why was quantum mechanics originated?', 'To answer the questions of physics', 'To revolutionize ancient physics', 'To answer the duality of light', 'To explain the nature of atoms', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'To explain the nature of atoms', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1430, 'What is the essence of this poem?', 'Physics is an interesting subject', 'Quantum mechanics can solve mysteries of physics', 'We don’t have any answers through physics', 'None of the above', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The poem revolves around quantum mechanics and the phenomena it can resolve by answering the question of what composes matter. It will also answer whether atoms are made of particles or light and solve the mysteries of physics.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1431, 'Which question does the verse “Alas, an answer, no one gave” refer to?', 'What is the photoelectric effect?', 'What object makes up all of us?', 'What are the dynamics of mechanics?', 'What are particles made of?', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The verse before the one in question inquires whether the tiny particles that make up an atom are waves or particles. The verse at hand suggests an unknown answer. Hence, the reality of particles is in question here, making D the correct answer.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1432, 'Based on this poem, which of the following statement is correct?', 'Light functions as both a wave and a particle.', 'Quantum mechanics originated due to the arising doubts about matter’s reality', 'Wave-particle duality describes the physical behavior of light and matter.', 'Newton\'s hypothesis prevailed for more than a century', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The two verses “Remember the double slit experiment, and photo-electric effect//Revolutionized Newtonian physics, and classical mechanics subject,” tell us that both experiments resulted in the revolution of Newtonian physics and classical mechanics. Therefore, both A and B are correct.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1433, 'What are the contributions of the double-slit experiment and the photo-electric effect?', 'They revolutionized Newtonian physics', 'They revolutionized classical mechanics', 'Both A & B', 'None of the above', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The two verses “Remember the double slit experiment, and photo-electric effect//Revolutionized Newtonian physics, and classical mechanics subject,” tell us that both experiments resulted in the revolution of Newtonian physics and classical mechanics. Therefore, both A and B are correct.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1434, 'What does the poet mean in verse “Waves and particles, they can be both or either”?', 'Matter can exist as waves, particles, or both', 'Matter exists in the form of waves', 'Matter exists in the form of particles', 'Matter can neither be in particle form nor wave form', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Based on this poem, atoms are neither clearly classsified as waves nor particles. Additionally, the verse “For all we know they might even be neither,” suggests that maybe atoms are made of neither. Therefore, matter can exist as waves, particles, or both', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
