(1438, 'Choose from the sentences (A - G) the one which fits in the gap 18', 'thrive in a changing environment when species that have adapted to their habitats lose their inherent advantages.', 'more frequent and extreme weather disasters such as flooding.', 'adjust to new surroundings when plants change their blooming times', 'such as flooding land and burning trees, but they also have long-lasting consequences like serious water contamination.', 'which can withstand higher temperatures, and compete with brook trout.', 'Wood thrushes fly up from the tropical forests of Central America every summer to their northern breeding grounds', 'eat flowers that are in bloom earlier in the year.', NULL, '5', 'This paragraph discusses brook trout and offers information regarding its habitat. The next sentence begins with non-native brown trout and the missing phrase states the competition of some specie with brook trout. Therefore, we can link the two phrases and fit this phrase in this space', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1439, 'Choose from the sentences (A - G) the one which fits in the gap 19', 'thrive in a changing environment when species that have adapted to their habitats lose their inherent advantages.', 'more frequent and extreme weather disasters such as flooding.', 'adjust to new surroundings when plants change their blooming times', 'such as flooding land and burning trees, but they also have long-lasting consequences like serious water contamination.', 'which can withstand higher temperatures, and compete with brook trout.', 'Wood thrushes fly up from the tropical forests of Central America every summer to their northern breeding grounds', 'eat flowers that are in bloom earlier in the year.', NULL, '2', 'The sentence begins with the causes of climate change-related issues, and the missing phrase further elaborates on these issues, which are extreme weather disasters like flooding. Hence, this phrase is suitable here.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1440, 'Choose from the sentences (A - G) the one which fits in the gap 20', 'thrive in a changing environment when species that have adapted to their habitats lose their inherent advantages.', 'more frequent and extreme weather disasters such as flooding.', 'adjust to new surroundings when plants change their blooming times', 'such as flooding land and burning trees, but they also have long-lasting consequences like serious water contamination.', 'which can withstand higher temperatures, and compete with brook trout.', 'Wood thrushes fly up from the tropical forests of Central America every summer to their northern breeding grounds', 'eat flowers that are in bloom earlier in the year.', NULL, '4', 'The second sentence of this paragraph is about rapid flood waters, whereas the missing phrase offers information about flooding and its consequences. Therefore, the phrase is appropriate here.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1441, 'Describes the discovery of Andromeda galaxy?', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract  C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The first paragraph of the extract describes the discovery. Edwin Hubble discovered the Andromeda galaxy in the 1920s after observing a nebula that was actually a galaxy.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1442, 'Informs that Milky Way is home to over 100 billion planets?', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract  C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The first paragraph discusses the Milky Way. It says that our galaxy, has over 100 billion planets and that Earth is a little speck in the cosmos.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1443, 'Argues how matter acquired the gravitational framework necessary for it to merge into the first galaxies?', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract  C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Paragraph 2 of the extract describes the phenomena. It says that theoretically, astronomers think that the massive tendrils of dark matter gave the matter the gravitational framework necessary for it to coalesce into the first galaxies in the early universe.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1444, 'Provides information of spiral galaxies that they feature a flat rotating disc and a spiral arm-adorned centre bulge.', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract  C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Paragraph 2 of the extract states that all known galaxies, more than two-thirds, are spirals. This galaxy features a flat rotating disc and a spiral arm-adorned centre bulge.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1445, 'Describes the ignition of earth’s earliest stars?', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract  C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The first paragraph of the extract describes the ignition. It says that according to astronomers, 180 million years after the big bang, the universe\'s earliest stars are thought to have ignited.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1446, 'Provides the reason why lenticular galaxies have this name?', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract  C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The first paragraph of the extract provides the reasons that because they resemble lenses, they are referred to be lenticular.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1447, 'Discusses the kind of galaxy that falls midway between spiral and elliptical galaxies?', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract  C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The first paragraph of the extract states that one of the lenticular galaxies is the Sombrero Galaxy. This kind of galaxy falls midway between spiral and elliptical galaxies.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1448, 'States the present age of the universe and the duration of time since it has rotated?', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract  C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The first paragraph of extract B states that when the universe rotated about 400 million years ago, or less than 3% of its present age, gravity shaped the early galaxies into their current shape.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1449, 'Differentiates between the sizes of dwarf elliptical galaxies and normal elliptical galaxies?', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract  C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Paragraph 2 of extract D states that dwarf elliptical galaxies are elliptical galaxies that are smaller than normal elliptical galaxies.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1450, 'Suggests that the number of stars in a galaxy is up to a trillion?', 'Extract A', 'Extract B', 'Extract C', 'Extract D', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The second paragraph of the extract states that Galaxies contain up to a million or a trillion stars and are vast systems of gas, dark matter, and primarily dust.', 101, NULL, 0, 1),
(1476, 'James travels by car from his house to his business office, which takes exactly 1 hour and 10 minutes. To pass the time, he listens to audio books. If he starts an audiobook at 7:30 AM as soon as he starts his car, then pauses it when he reaches the office at 8:40 AM, when will the audiobook end if it is 6 hours long and he listens to it only during his commute?', 'After 45 days', 'After 60 days', 'After 54 days', 'After 72 days', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Every day, James listens to the book for 70 minutes or 1 hour and 10 minutes. Therefore, 6 hours/1 hour and 10 minutes = 5.4 days. Since James cannot split his journey between days, he will finish his book on his 6th day of journey.', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1477, 'On Friday, Nathan came back from a trip and noticed that his wall clock, which had been left running, is 2 hours slow. Remembering that he had set the clock to the correct time at noon on Monday, and the clock now reads 4 PM Friday, what is the actual time now?', '4 PM Friday', '5 PM Friday', '6 PM Friday', '7 PM Friday', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Nathan\'s wall clock was set correctly at noon Monday and it is now 28 hours slow. Thus, it lost 2 hours in 116 hours (From Monday 12 PM to Friday 4 PM = 5*24 - 8 = 116 hours). Therefore, 1 hour is lost every 58 hours (116/2). At present, it is 2 hours slow so the current time = 4 PM + 2 hours = 6 PM Friday.', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1478, 'Carl is a teacher who scheduled a Zoom meeting with his students for 2 hours. However, his clock is 10 minutes fast. If he started the meeting at 10 AM according to his clock, what time will it be according to a correctly set clock when the meeting ends?', '11:50 AM', '12:00 PM', '12:10 PM', '12:20 PM', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Carl\'s clock is 10 minutes fast. So, when it reads 10 AM in his clock, it would be 9:50 AM in the correct clock. Therefore, the meeting starting at 10 AM in his clock will actually be starting at 9:50 AM in a correct clock, and hence, will end 2 hours later which is 11:50 AM + 20 minutes = 12:10 PM.', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1479, 'Clara works in a chocolate factory. She is a quality inspector and time is an important aspect in her job. She must inspect a chocolate box every 15 minutes. How many boxes will Clara inspect in an 8-hour shift?', '30 boxes', '32 boxes', '48 boxes', '50 boxes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Clara works 8 hours = 480 minutes. Since she inspects a box every 15 minutes, 480 / 15 = 32 boxes she will inspect during her 8-hour shift', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1480, 'Zoya is a businesswoman who has meetings in different cities. If she takes a train that travels at a speed of 50 km/hr and thereafter continues with a car at 20 km/hr. If she spends twice as much time in the car as in the train and the total time of travel is 10 hours, how much time did she spend in the train?', '6.66 hours', '2.5 hours', '3.33 hours', '4 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Let\'s suppose she spends \'T\' hours on the train. Since she spends double time in the car, she spends \'2T\' hours on the car. Therefore, T + 2T = 10 hours => T = 3.33 hours. So, she spends approximately 3.33 hours on the train.', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1481, 'Jackson delivers pizzas for a local pizzeria. He begins his shift at 5 PM and ends at 10 PM, taking 10 minutes to deliver each pizza. If he starts his first delivery exactly at 5 PM and does not take any break, how many pizzas can he deliver in his shift?', '25 pizzas', '30 pizzas', '50 pizzas', '60 pizzas', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Jackson works 5 hours = 300 minutes. Since he takes 10 minutes to deliver each pizza, he can make 300 / 10 = 30 deliveries during his shift.', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1482, 'Luke, an English teacher, spends 2 minutes checking each exam paper. If he spent a total of 5 hours checking papers, how many papers did he check?', '100 papers', '120 papers', '150 papers', '200 papers', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Luke spends 5 hours = 300 minutes checking papers. Since he takes 2 minutes to check a paper, he checks 300 / 2 = 150 papers in total.', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1483, 'Billy runs a bakery and bakes apple pies daily. It takes 10 minutes to bake each apple pie plus 5 minutes to cool down before he can bake the next one. How many pies can he bake in 8 hours if he can only bake one at a time?', '32 pies', '40 pies', '48 pies', '64 pies', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Billy spends 8 hours = 480 minutes baking pies. Since it takes 10 minutes to bake and 5 minutes to cool down, total time for one pie is 15 minutes. So, he can bake 480 / 15 = 32 pies during his 8-hour shift.', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1484, 'A motor ship travels with a speed of 40 km/hr. The ship departed at 10 AM and after travelling for a certain amount of time, it docked at a port. If the ship stayed at the port for 2 hours, and then continued its journey, finally arriving at its destination exactly at 5 PM. How many hours was the ship in motion?', '4 hours', '5 hours', '6 hours', '7 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'From 10 AM to 5 PM, it\'s 7 hours. If we subtract the 2 hours the ship was docked, we get 7 - 2 = 5 hours. Therefore, the ship was in motion for 5 hours.', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1485, 'Nora went shopping and spent 3 hours in the ‘Book Bazaar’. Later, she spent half as much time in the ‘Jacket Junction’. After that, she spent twice as time in the ‘Cosmetic Corner’ as she had spent in the ‘Jacket Junction’. If she entered the mall at 1 PM, when did she leave the mall?', '7 PM', '8 PM', '9 PM', '10 PM', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Nora spent 3 hours in ‘Book Bazaar’, half of that in ‘Jacket Junction’ is 3/2 = 1.5 hours and then twice as much in the ‘Cosmetic Corner’ is 2*1.5 = 3 hours. A total of 3 + 1.5 + 3 = 7.5 hours. So, if she entered the mall at 1 PM, she left at 1 PM + 7.5 hours = 8:30 PM.', 89, NULL, 0, 1),
(1486, 'Clara and Darcy promised each other to meet in a park for a pizza party at the age of 40. If Clara is 4 years older than Darcy, how many years will Clara have to wait when Darcy turns 30?', '6 years', '10 years', '14 years', '8 years', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'When Darcy turns 30, Clara will be 34. Clara will have to wait 6 more years to turn 40. But they made a promise to meet when both are 40, so Clara has to wait until Darcy turns 40, which is in 10 years. Therefore, Clara will have to wait 10 + 6 = 16 years.', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1487, 'Freda and Eliza decided to start a chocolate business. If Eliza age is a third of Freda\'s and their ages sum up to 48 years, how old will Eliza be when she is half as old as Freda?', '24 years', '16 years', '20 years', '18 years', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Currently, Freda is 36 years old and Eliza is 12. Eliza will be half as old as Freda when Freda is 32 and Eliza is 16.', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1488, 'James started his glass jar import business at age 22 and retired at 60. If his business grew linearly over the years, at what age was the company half as successful as when he retired?', '41', '39', '40', '42', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'His business life spanned 38 years (60 - 22). The business would be half as successful at the midpoint in time, which was 19 years into his career (22 + 19 = 41).', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1489, 'Roy, who is currently 30, has a son who is 4. How old will Roy\'s son be when the sum of their ages is 90?', '28', '30', '32', '34', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'When the sum of their ages is 90, Roy will be 60 because he is currently 30. So Roy\'s son will be 90 - 60 = 30 years old.', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1490, 'Henry buys an apple for $2 each day. His friend Peter is 3 years older than him and buys 2 apples per day. If the cost remains the same, how much more will Peter have spent on apples when they are 35 years old?', '$2190', '$2555', '$2920', '$3285', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Peter spends $4 a day on apples. The difference between Peter\'s and Henry\'s daily spending is $2. Over the course of a year (365 days), Peter will spend an extra $730. Therefore, since Peter starts his routine three years earlier than Henry, Peter will have spent an extra $2190 on apples by the time they turn 35.', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1491, 'If John started a used book business at the age of 24 and his success doubled every 5 years. How many times more successful is his business when John is 49 than when he started?', '32 times', '64 times', '16 times', '128 times', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'John\'s business doubles success every 5 years. Therefore, at 29, it is 2 times more successful, at 34 it is 4 times, at 39 it is 8 times, at 44 it is 16 times and at 49 it is 32 times more successful than when he started.', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1492, 'Carl invests in a car trading company at the age of 25 and his investment doubles every year. How old will he be when his investment is 64 times the original amount?', '31', '30', '32', '33', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Carl\'s investment doubles every year, so it takes 6 years for his investment to increase 64 times (since 2 to the power of 6 equals 64). Therefore, Carl will be 25 + 6 = 31 years old.', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1493, 'Alice, a language teacher, has twice the age of her student Emma. If the sum of their ages is 60 years, how old will Alice be when her age is four times the age of Emma?', '40 years', '50 years', '60 years', '70 years', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Alice has twice Emma\'s age; therefore, Alice\'s age is 40 and Emma\'s is 20. In future, when Alice is four times Emma\'s age, Emma will be 25, and Alice will be 50.', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1494, 'If Nathan bought a house at 25 years old for $100,000 and the value of the house increased by $3,000 each year, how old will he be when the house is worth $205,000?', '60 years', '55 years', '58 years', '56 years', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The house increases by $3,000 each year, so for it to be worth $205,000 (which is $105,000 more than the purchase amount), it would need to increase for 35 years. Therefore, Nathan would be 60 years old (25 + 35).', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1495, 'John trains for 4 hours a day while Peter trains for 3 hours. If John began training at the age of 16 and Peter at 14, how much more time will John have trained than Peter by the time they turn 26?', '3650 hours', '2920 hours', '4380 hours', '5110 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Each year has 365 days. The time when both started training until they turn 26 is 10 years for John (10 * 365 * 4 = 14600 hours), and 12 years for Peter (12 * 365 * 3 = 13140 hours). Therefore, John has trained 14600 - 13140 = 1460 hours more.', 103, NULL, 0, 1),
(1496, 'Alice has 600 pens. She loans 20% of her pens to Harrison. How many pens does Alice have left?', '480 pens', '520 pens', '540 pens', '580 pens', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '20% of 600 pens is 120 pens. Therefore, Alice has 600 - 120 = 480 pens left.', 64, NULL, 0, 1),
(1497, 'Zoya got a job as a teacher with an initial salary of $50,000. After one year, she received a 4% raise. How much is her salary after the raise?', '$52,000', '$52,500', '$53,000', '$54,000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '4% of $50,000 is $2,000. Therefore, her salary is now $52,000.', 64, NULL, 0, 1),
(1498, 'Jackson bought a box of chocolates. Due to a promotional offer, he received an additional 25% chocolates in the box. If the original box contained 50 chocolates, how many chocolates are there in the box now?', '60 chocolates', '62 chocolates', '65 chocolates', '70 chocolates', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '25% of 50 chocolates is 12.5. Therefore, Jackson now has 50 + 12.5 = 62.5 chocolates. Since there cannot be a half chocolate he gets an extra piece, making it 63 chocolates.', 64, NULL, 0, 1),
(1499, 'James invested some money in his brother\'s car business. Over a year, his investment increased by 15%. If his initial investment was $20,000, how much is his investment after a year?', '$22,200', '$23,000', '$24,000', '$25,000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '15% of $20,000 is $3,000. So, his investment after a year is $20,000 + $3,000 = $23,000.', 64, NULL, 0, 1);
INSERT INTO `question` (`id`, `question`, `option_1`, `option_2`, `option_3`, `option_4`, `option_5`, `option_6`, `option_7`, `option_8`, `correct_option`, `explanation`, `tst_id`, `marks`, `nvq`, `status`) VALUES
(1500, 'Diana ordered a pizza that was cut into 8 equal slices. She ate 50% of the pizza. How many slices are left?', '2 slices', '3 slices', '4 slices', '5 slices', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '50% of 8 slices is 4 slices. Hence, there are 8 - 4 = 4 slices left.', 64, NULL, 0, 1),
(1501, 'John is packing books into boxes for his move to college. If one box holds 20 books and John has packed 75% of his books, how many books has he packed if he has 280 books in total?', '200 books', '210 books', '220 books', '230 books', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', '75% of 280 books is 210 books. So, John has packed 210 books.', 64, NULL, 0, 1),
(1502, 'If Georgia saves 6% of her monthly salary of $5,000 for a vacation fund, how much money will be in her vacation fund after twelve months?', '$3,600', '$3,500', '$3,400', '$3,300', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '6% of $5,000 is $300. Therefore, she will save $300 x 12 months = $3,600 in a year.', 64, NULL, 0, 1),
(1503, 'Fearful of missing his train, Carl increased his speed during his walk to the park by 30%. If his normal speed is 5km/hour, what was his speed after the increase?', '6.5km/hr', '6km/hr', '6.3km/hr', '5.8km/hr', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '30% of 5km/hr is 1.5km/hr. So, his speed after the increase is 5 + 1.5 = 6.5km/hr.', 64, NULL, 0, 1),
(1504, 'Ella runs a cake business where she sells chocolate cakes and apple cakes. If she sells 60% of her cakes as chocolate cakes and 500 cakes in total, how many apple cakes does she sell?', '200 cakes', '250 cakes', '300 cakes', '350 cakes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '60% of 500 cakes is 300 cakes, which are chocolate. Therefore, Ella sells 500 - 300 = 200 apple cakes.', 64, NULL, 0, 1),
(1505, 'Winston bought a car and after a few years sold it. If the selling price was 80% of the purchase price and the purchase price was $25,000, find the selling price of the car?', '$19,500', '$20,000', '$20,500', '$21,000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', '80% of $25,000 is $20,000. Therefore, Winston sold the car for $20,000.', 64, NULL, 0, 1),
(1506, 'Alice works in a jacket store and records how many jackets are sold per hour. If she sold 4.5 jackets during the first hour and this rate increased by 0.2 every other hour, how many jackets did she sell in 5 hours?', '22.1 jackets', '24.1 jackets', '22.8 jackets', '24.3 jackets', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'In the first hour, Alice sold 4.5 jackets. In the second hour, she increased the rate by 0.2 so she sold 4.7 jackets. In the third hour, the rate did not increase so she sold only 4.5 jackets. This cycle repeats for the rest of the time. So, Alice sold 4.5 + 4.7 + 4.5 + 4.7 + 4.4 jackets, which total 22.8 jackets.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1507, 'Josh has a chocolate business. If the business makes a profit margin of 0.45 for each chocolate sold, how much will Josh make from selling 345 chocolates in dollars?', '155.25 dollars', '157.50 dollars', '146.50 dollars', '152.25 dollars', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Since the profit margin for each chocolate is 0.45 dollars, Josh will make 345*0.45=155.25 dollars from selling 345 chocolates.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1508, 'Lucy is a teacher who grades her students\' books. If she spends 0.35 hours grading each book and she has 29 books to grade, how much time would she take in total?', '10.25 hours', '12.4 hours', '10.15 hours', '11.25 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The total time Lucy would spend grading is 29*0.35=10.15 hours.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1509, 'John bought a car for $15,500.00. If the value of the car depreciates each year by 0.08, how much would the car be worth after 2 years in dollars?', '13149.68 dollars', '13207.44 dollars', '13116.64 dollars', '13156.24 dollars', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The car would depreciate by 8% each year, so after the first year it would be worth 15500*0.92=14260 dollars. After the second year, it would be worth 14260*0.92=13149.68 dollars.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1510, 'Henry went apple picking and picked 4.3 bags of apples. If each bag weighs 0.75 kg, how much do all the apples weigh in kilograms?', '3.225 kg', '3.15 kg', '3.24 kg', '3.30 kg', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total weight of the apples is 4.3*0.75=3.225 kg.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1511, 'Eliza run a cake shop. If her house is 12.45 km from the shop and the car she drives moves at a speed of 0.75 km/minute, how long will she take to travel to the shop in minutes?', '18.60 minutes', '16.60 minutes', '17.70 minutes', '16.60 minutes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The time Eliza would take to travel to the shop is 12.45/0.75=16.60 minutes.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1512, 'Roy ordered a box of pens online. If the shipping cost for the pens is 0.65 dollars and the pens cost 32 dollars, how much will he pay in total?', '32.65 dollars', '32.95 dollars', '33.05 dollars', '33.35 dollars', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total cost is the cost of the pens plus the shipping cost. Therefore, he will pay 32+0.65=32.65 dollars.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1513, 'Emma is a train driver and drives for 5.6 hours in a day. If the train uses 0.75 liters of diesel per hour, how much diesel will her train have used in liters?', '4.2 liters', '5.2 liters', '4.0 liters', '6.0 liters', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total diesel used is 5.6*0.75=4.2 liters.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1514, 'Georgia works at a pizza shop. If she slices each pizza into 8 pieces and she has 4.5 pizzas, how many slices will she have?', '36 slices', '38 slices', '34 slices', '40 slices', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total slices of pizza Georgia will have is 8*4.5=36 slices.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1515, 'James has a glass of water. The glass\'s capacity is 0.345 liters. If James drank 0.12 of the water, how much water is left in the glass in liters?', '0.225 liters', '0.216 liters', '0.211 liters', '0.201 liters', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The amount of water left after James drank some of it is 0.345-0.12=0.225 liters.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1516, 'Matilda bought a jar of cookies each costs 0.20 dollars. If the total cost was 2 dollars, how many cookies can she get from the jar?', '10 cookies', '12 cookies', '8 cookies', '15 cookies', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total cookies Matilda will have is 2/0.2=10 cookies.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1517, 'John is a ship captain. If his salary increases by 0.03 every year, how much would he be earning after 5 years if his initial salary is 6000 dollars per year?', '6890.62 dollars', '6905.31 dollars', '6978.74 dollars', '6956.42 dollars', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'John\'s salary after one year would be 6000 + (6000*0.03)=6180 dollars. Using the same method for the remaining four years, his salary after 5 years would be approximately 6905.31 dollars per year.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1518, 'Clara made $0.09 profit on each pencil she sold. If she sold 232 pencils, how much total profit did she make in dollars?', '20.88 dollars', '21.00 dollars', '21.15 dollars', '20.05 dollars', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total profit Clara made is 232*0.09=20.88 dollars.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
(1519, 'Nathan has a park cleaning business. If the job pays $0.59 per square meter and the park is 2000 square meters, how much will Nathan be paid in total?', '1184 dollars', '1180 dollars', '1200 dollars', '1170 dollars', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total pay Nathan will receive is 2000*0.59=1180 dollars.', 66, NULL, 0, 1),
