(1576, 'One of the following sentences is true. Which is it?', 'Zoya is 14 years old', 'Sam is 1 year older than Zoya', 'Bobby is 2 years older than Natasha', 'Dennis is 18 years old', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Natasha is 15 years old. Therefore, Zoya must also be 15 years old because they are twins. Bobby is 2 years younger than Zoya, therefore, Bobby is 13 years old. And since Dennis is 3 years older than Bobby, Dennis is 16 years old. Therefore, the answer is Option D.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1577, 'How many km does Frank need to drive to be exactly east of his workplace?', '1 KM', '2 KM', '3 KM', '4 KM', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Frank has to drive 4 more km to be directly east of his workplace. Therefore, the answer is Option D.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1578, 'Lloyd walks into a pizza parlor on a Monday. He orders a Margherita pizza but adds extra Mozzarella and Anchovies as optional toppings. He also orders a Veggie pizza. How much does this cost him?', '$35.18', '$33.98', '$34.78', '$32.68', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Margherita pizza (with extra Mozzarella and Anchovies) = $16.99 + $1.00 + $1.00 = $18.99. Veggie pizza = $14.99. Total = $18.99 + $14.99 = $33.98. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1579, 'If Jenson leaves the house at 8:00 am to get to the university, what time will Sam need to leave to arrive at the same time as Jenson?', '7:00 am', '7:30 am', '8:30 am', '9:00 am', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Jenson skates at a pace of 9 km/hr i.e. 4.5 km in 30 mins. If the university is 18 km away, then it takes him 30 × 4 = 120 mins = 2 hours to get to the university. Sam skates at a pace of 6 km/hr. If the university is 18 km away, then it takes him 1 hour × 3 = 3 hours to get to the university. Therefore, Sam has to leave 60 minutes earlier than Jenson in order to arrive at the same time. Therefore, Sam has to leave at 7:00 am. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1580, 'If the quoted passage above is true, which of the following best describes the mistake in Austin’s reasoning?', 'Practicing a skill doesn\'t necessarily mean you will master it', 'Austin might not be able to master the skill as quickly as Tom even with the same amount of practice', 'Tom does not practice enough to master the skill', 'Austin is naturally better at mastering skills than Tom', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Austin: If I practice just as much as Tom, I will be able to master the skill just as quickly as him. Even though the passage indicates that practice leads to better mastery of a skill, it also suggests that some people can master a skill faster than others with the same amount of practice. Hence, it\'s not guaranteed that Austin will master the skill as quickly as Tom even if he practices as much as Tom does. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1581, 'If the quoted passage above is true, which of the following best describes the mistake in Bobby’s reasoning?', 'Insurance provides no financial protection against damage from accidents.', 'Bobby assumed that he is definitely going bankrupt simply because he had an accident without insurance.', 'Car repairs are not expensive enough to cause bankruptcy.', 'Bobby assumed that his car is not damaged because he had insurance.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Bobby simply assumed that he is definitely going bankrupt due to the accident and no insurance. Although it is known that not having insurance is likely to cause financial distress when an accident occurs, it doesn\'t mean that bankruptcy is inevitable. Bobby may still be able to pay for the damages out of pocket or find another solution, despite not having insurance. Therefore, the correct answer is Option B.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1582, 'Which of the following statements is false?', 'Paris is in France', 'All cities in France have a significant architectural heritage', 'Paris does not have significant architectural heritage', 'Paris, as a city in France, has a significant architectural heritage', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Since the passage states that all cities in France have a significant architectural heritage, and since Paris is a city in France, it follows that Paris must also have a significant architectural heritage. Therefore, the statement in option c that \'Paris does not have significant architectural heritage\' is false.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1583, 'Alice buys 3 Egg Benedicts on Monday and also a Pesto Chicken sandwich with tomato, lettuce, and onions. If she pays with a $50 note, how much change should she receive?', '$21.40', '$19.80', '$20.50', '$21.80', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'On Monday, Alice can buy 1 Egg Benedict and receive the other ones half off. Therefore, 3 Egg Benedicts cost $10.00 + 2 x ($10.00 ÷ 2) = $20.00. A Pesto Chicken sandwich with tomato, lettuce, and onions costs: $12.00 + ($0.60 × 3) = $13.80. However, after the 10% discount on Monday, the Pesto Chicken sandwich costs: $13.80 × 90% = $12.42. Total = $20.00 + $12.42 = $32.42. Therefore, change from $50 note = $50 – $32.42 = $17.58. Therefore, the answer is Option A.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1584, 'Who is the 3rd heaviest among Zoya, Alice, Jenson, and Lloyd?', 'Zoya', 'Alice', 'Jenson', 'Lloyd', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Zoya is lighter than Alice but heavier than Jenson. Lloyd is the heaviest. Therefore, the order must be: Lloyd, Alice, Zoya, Jenson. Therefore, Zoya came 3rd. Therefore, the answer is Option A', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1585, 'Which of the following outcomes is not possible for Philips’s next week if he solved 4 bugs this week?', 'Philips will solve 8 bugs next week and receive a bonus.', 'Philips will solve 4 bugs next week', 'Philips receives a bonus in 2 weeks’ time', 'Philips has to attend a training session next week', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Philips solved 4 bugs this week, which is more than the threshold of 3 for attending a training session in the next week. Therefore, it is not possible for Philips to attend a training session next week.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1586, 'How long will it take for Natasha and John to sew the 9 costumes together?', '14 mins', '21 mins', '28 mins', '35 mins', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Natasha sews 3 costumes in 7 minutes while John sews 1 costume in 7 minutes. Therefore, together, they can sew 4 costumes in 7 minutes. Hence, they will sew 9 costumes in 21 minutes. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1587, 'If the start-up requires a candidate with at least 10 years of work experience and a degree in Computer Science, who should they consider hiring?', 'Sam', 'Alice', 'James', 'None of them', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The start-up requires a candidate with at least 10 years of work experience and a degree in Computer Science. Sam is the only candidate who meets both requirements. Hence, the answer is Option A.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1588, 'Every Wednesday, Natasha buys a Chicken Caesar salad for dinner. She refrains from making any other purchase from the restaurant during the week. How much does Natasha spend per year at Cafe GoodEats?', '$780', '$832', '$884', '$936', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'A Chicken Caesar salad costs $16.00. Therefore, Natasha spends $16.00 per week at Cafe GoodEats. Hence, as there are 52 weeks in a year, Natasha spends $16 x 52 = $832 per year. The answer is option b.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1589, 'If the quoted passage above is true, which of the following shows the mistake that Evan made in his reasoning?', 'He assumed that Tom only had one baseball cap that he lost', 'The cap that he saw might not be Tom\'s as other people could also own a blue cap with a basketball team logo', 'Even if the cap that Evan saw is blue, it might have different team logo on it', 'Tom might not have lost his cap yesterday, he may have lost it a while ago', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Just because Evan saw a cap that matched the description of the cap that Tom lost does not mean that the cap is Tom\'s. Someone else could also own a blue cap with a basketball team logo.', 111, NULL, 0, 1),
(1610, 'A research paper claims that listening to classical music improves cognitive abilities. Alice: I\'m going to start listening to classical music while studying, so I will become a genius in no time. Which of the following shows the mistake in Alice\'s reasoning?', 'Alice may not enjoy listening to classical music.', 'Alice might not understand the complex compositions in classical music.', 'Alice\'s cognitive abilities may already be at a high level.', 'Alice may need to listen to classical music for an extended period of time before seeing any improvement.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Alice: I\'m going to start listening to classical music while studying, so I will become a genius in no time.While the research paper suggests that listening to classical music improves cognitive abilities, it does not guarantee immediate or instant results. Alice may need to listen to classical music for an extended period of time before seeing any noticeable improvement in her cognitive abilities.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1611, 'Louis can solve a math problem in 20 minutes. How long does it take for him to solve 5 similar math problems?', '80 minutes', '100 minutes', '120 minutes', '140 minutes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'If Louis can solve 1 math problem in 20 minutes, then it would take him 20 minutes x 5 = 100 minutes to solve 5 similar math problems.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1612, 'John read an article claiming that all introverted people are shy. Based on this, he concludes that his friend Amelia, who is introverted, must also be shy. Which of the following options highlights the mistake made in John\'s reasoning?', 'Assuming that being introverted automatically means being shy', 'Assuming that all shy people are introverted', 'Assuming that Amelia is an introverted person', 'Assuming that John\'s friend Natasha is also introverted', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The mistake in John\'s reasoning is assuming that all introverted people are shy. This oversimplifies the concept of introversion and ignores the possibility that introverted individuals can have varying levels of shyness or social comfort.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1613, 'Bobby, Georgia, Lloyd, and Jessie are all competing in a math competition. Whoever solves the most complex equation correctly wins. Georgia solves 5 equations correctly, Jessie solves 4 equations correctly, Bobby solves 3 equations correctly, and Lloyd solves 2 equations correctly. Who wins the competition?', 'Georgia', 'Jessie', 'Bobby', 'Lloyd', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Georgia solved the most equations correctly, so she wins the competition.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1614, 'If Bobby can complete a task in 4 hours and Zoya can complete the same task in 6 hours, how long will it take for them to complete the task together?', '2.4 hours', '3.6 hours', '6.4 hours', '9.6 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'To find how long it takes for them to complete the task together, we need to calculate the reciprocal of their individual rates and add them together. Bobby\'s rate is 1/4 and Zoya\'s rate is 1/6. Adding them together gives us 1/4 + 1/6 = 3/12 + 2/12 = 5/12. The reciprocal of 5/12 is 12/5, which equals 2.4. Therefore, it will take them 2.4 hours (or 2 hours and 24 minutes) to complete the task together.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1615, 'Bobby, Georgia, Lloyd, and Jessie are all participating in a debate competition. Each person gives a speech, and the judges rate their speeches on a scale of 1 to 10. The scores are as follows: Bobby - 8, Georgia - 6, Lloyd - 7, Jessie - 9. Who receives the highest overall score?', 'Bobby', 'Georgia', 'Lloyd', 'Jessie', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Jessie receives the highest overall score with a score of 9.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1616, 'Five college students - Alia, Daisy, Frank, Tom, and Kyle - are participating in a logic competition. Each student represents a different college - A, B, C, D, and E. Based on the clues given, determine which college each student represents.\n1. The student from college B is not Alia or Kyle.\n2. Frank represents college D.\n3. Daisy does not represent college C.\n4. The student from college E is either Tom or Kyle.\nWhich college does Alia represent?', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'E', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Based on the clues given, we can determine the following:\n- Frank represents college D.\n- The student from college E is either Tom or Kyle.\n- Daisy does not represent college C.\nSince all the colleges have been accounted for, Alia must represent college A.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1617, 'Clara scored 90% on her math test last month. This month, she scored 80%. What is the percentage decrease in her score?', '10%', '11.11%', '12.5%', '20%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'To find the percentage decrease, we subtract the new value (80) from the original value (90), then divide the result by the original value and multiply by 100. Percentage decrease = ((90-80)/90) * 100 = 10/90 * 100 = 1/9 * 100 = 11.11%. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1618, 'In a math contest, there are 6 participants: Austin, Daisy, Nathan, and Nora. Austin finished before Daisy. Nathan finished after Daisy. Nora finished before Nathan. Who finished first?', 'Austin', 'Daisy', 'Nathan', 'Nora', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'By the given statements, the order of finishing is: Nora, Nathan, Daisy, Austin. Therefore, Nora finished first.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1619, 'Marry wants to buy new outfits. She has 4 skirts, 6 tops, and 5 pairs of shoes. How many different combinations of outfits can she create?', '80', '100', '120', '150', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Total combinations = 4 × 6 × 5 = 120 combinations. Therefore, the answer is Option C.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1620, 'A recent study found that students who study in a quiet environment perform better on exams compared to those who study in a noisy environment. Sam: I always study in complete silence, so I am guaranteed to get the highest grades on my exams. Which of the following shows the mistake in Sam’s reasoning?', 'Sam may not be studying effectively even if he is in a quiet environment.', 'Sam might not be the only student who studies in complete silence.', 'Sam may have other factors affecting his exam performance.', 'Sam might find it difficult to concentrate in a quiet environment.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Sam: I always study in complete silence, so I am guaranteed to get the highest grades on my exams.The quoted study suggests that students who study in a quiet environment perform better on exams, but it does not guarantee that all students who study in complete silence will automatically get the highest grades. There may be other factors influencing Sam\'s exam performance.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1621, 'Myra spent 1/3 of her monthly salary on groceries. If her salary is $1500, how much money did she spend on groceries?', '$300', '$400', '$500', '$600', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'If Myra spent 1/3 of her salary on groceries, then she spent $1500 x 1/3 = $500 on groceries.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1622, 'John and Flora are participating in a chess tournament. In the first round, John won 3 out of 5 matches, while Flora won 2 out of 4 matches. Who has a higher winning percentage?', 'John', 'Flora', 'They have the same winning percentage', 'Cannot be determined', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To compare their winning percentages, we need to calculate the ratio of matches won to matches played for each player. John\'s winning percentage is 3/5 = 0.6 (or 60%), while Flora\'s winning percentage is 2/4 = 0.5 (or 50%). Therefore, John has a higher winning percentage than Flora.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1623, 'NatashaandGeorgiaare both studying for a Math test. Natasha has solved 10 practice problems, while Georgia has solved 15 practice problems. If their goal is to solve a total of 30 practice problems before the test, how many more problems does Natasha need to solve?', '5', '10', '15', '20', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Natasha has solved 10 practice problems, and Georgia has solved 15 practice problems. The total number of problems solved so far is 10 + 15 = 25. Natasha needs to solve 30 - 25 = 5 more problems to reach the goal of 30 problems.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1624, 'Myra thinks that creativity is an innate trait that cannot be developed through practice and effort. Amelia disagrees and believes that creativity can be cultivated and improved over time. If both Myra and Amelia hold their perspectives, whose reasoning is correct?', 'Myra only', 'Amelia only', 'Both Myra and Amelia', 'Neither Myra nor Amelia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Myra: Myra believes that creativity is an innate trait, meaning it is something you are born with and cannot be developed through practice or effort. However, research has shown that creativity can be cultivated and improved through various techniques and exercises. Therefore, Myra\'s reasoning is incorrect. Amelia: Amelia\'s belief that creativity can be cultivated and improved over time is supported by evidence and studies. By engaging in creative activities, thinking outside the box, and practicing creative thinking techniques, individuals can enhance their creativity. Therefore, Amelia\'s reasoning is correct. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1625, 'Sally bought some books for her college courses. Each book cost $30 and she spent a total of $450 on books. How many books did Sally buy?', '10', '12', '14', '16', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'If each book costs $30 and the total cost of all the books Sally bought is $450, she can divide the total cost by the cost of each book to find the number of books. 450 / 30 = 15. Therefore, Sally bought 15 books.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1626, 'Bobby is training for a marathon. On the first day, he ran 6 miles. Each day after that, he increased his distance by 1.5 miles. If Bobby continues this pattern, how many miles will he run on the 10th day?', '15 miles', '16.5 miles', '18 miles', '20 miles', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Bobby ran 6 miles on the first day. Each day, he adds 1.5 miles to his distance. Therefore, on the 10th day, he will run 6 + (1.5 * 9) = 18 miles.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1627, 'Zoya and Stella are planning a road trip. On the first day, they drive 200 miles. Each day after that, they drive 20% more miles than the previous day. If they continue this pattern, how many miles will they have driven after 5 days?', '290 miles', '320 miles', '360 miles', '400 miles', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'On the first day, Zoya and Stella drive 200 miles. Each day, they add 20% more miles to their distance. Therefore, after 5 days, they will have driven a total of 200 + (200 * 0.2) + (200 * 0.2^2) + (200 * 0.2^3) + (200 * 0.2^4) = 400 miles.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1628, 'In a recent study at XYZ University, it was found that 40% of college students own a laptop. Therefore, it can be concluded that the majority of college students own a laptop.', 'Assuming that all college students were surveyed', 'Assuming that 40% is a representative sample of all college students', 'Assuming that college students who don\'t own a laptop are not interested in technology', 'Assuming that the study\'s sample size was sufficient', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The mistake in the reasoning is assuming that the 40% of college students surveyed accurately represents the entire population of college students. This may not be the case as the sample size might not be representative or the sample may be biased towards certain demographics.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1629, 'Sam believes that studying for 5 hours every day will guarantee him a perfect score on the upcoming exam. Jenson, on the other hand, thinks that just attending the lectures and taking notes will be enough. If both Sam and Jenson follow their respective strategies, whose reasoning is correct?', 'Sam only', 'Jenson only', 'Both Sam and Jenson', 'Neither Sam nor Jenson', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Sam: Sam believes that studying for 5 hours every day will guarantee him a perfect score. However, this assumption may not always hold true as different individuals have different learning abilities and strategies. Therefore, Sam\'s reasoning is incorrect. Jenson: Jenson\'s belief that attending the lectures and taking notes will be enough is not a strong strategy for guaranteeing a perfect score. It is important to complement lecture attendance with additional studying and practice. Therefore, Jenson\'s reasoning is also incorrect. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1630, 'There are four friends - Tom, Alia, Frank, and Daisy. They each have a different favorite color - blue, red, green, and yellow. Based on the clues given, determine each person\'s favorite color.\n1. The person whose favorite color is blue is not Daisy.\n2. Tom\'s favorite color is either red or green.\n3. Frank likes the color yellow.\n4. Alia\'s favorite color is not green.\nWhat is Daisy\'s favorite color?', 'Blue', 'Red', 'Green', 'Yellow', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Based on the clues given, we can determine the following:\n- Frank\'s favorite color is yellow.\n- Tom\'s favorite color is either red or green.\n- Alia\'s favorite color is not green.\nSince all the colors have been accounted for, Daisy\'s favorite color must be blue.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1631, 'Bill,Philips,andGeorgiaalltakea philosophy course. Bill has read 100 pages, Philips has read 120 pages, and Georgia has read 80 pages. If their goal is to read a total of 300 pages before the exam, how many more pages does Bill need to read?', '50', '70', '100', '120', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Bill has read 100 pages, Philips has read 120 pages, and Georgia has read 80 pages. The total number of pages read so far is 100 + 120 + 80 = 300. Bill needs to read 300 - 300 = 0 more pages to reach the goal of 300 pages.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1632, 'Myra can climb a tree in 45 seconds. If Daisy can climb the same tree in 60 seconds, how much faster is Myra in climbing the tree?', '10 seconds', '15 seconds', '20 seconds', '25 seconds', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Myra takes 45 seconds to climb the tree, while Daisy takes 60 seconds. Therefore, Myra is faster by 60 - 45 = 15 seconds. Hence, the answer is Option C.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1633, 'In a group of 8 students, Austin is taller than Nathan. Daisy is shorter than Nora. Nathan is taller than Daisy. Who is the shortest?', 'Austin', 'Nathan', 'Daisy', 'Nora', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'By the given statements, the order of height from shortest to tallest is: Daisy, Nathan, Austin, Nora. Therefore, Daisy is the shortest.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1634, 'Nathan can solve a math problem in 2 minutes, and Jenson can solve the same problem in 3 minutes. If they work together, how long will they take to solve the problem?', '1 minute', '1.2 minutes', '1.5 minutes', '1.8 minutes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Nathan can solve the problem in 2 minutes, and Jenson can solve it in 3 minutes. Therefore, their combined work rate is 1/2 + 1/3 = 5/6. To solve the problem, they need to complete 1 unit of work, which takes 6/5 minutes. Hence, the answer is Option D.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1635, 'Billowns3books,5pensand4pencils. How many different combinations of stationary can he create?', '100', '120', '150', '180', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Total combinations = 3 × 5 × 4 = 60 combinations. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1636, 'Nathan is planning to distribute some candies equally among his friends. If he has a total of 60 candies and he wants to give each friend 5 candies, how many friends does Nathan have?', '10', '12', '14', '16', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'If Nathan wants to give each friend 5 candies and he has a total of 60 candies, he can divide the total number of candies by the number of candies given to each friend to find the number of friends. 60 / 5 = 12. Therefore, Nathan has 12 friends.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1637, 'Chris, Sally, and Clara are three college students. If Chris is taller than Sally and Clara is shorter than Chris, who is the shortest among the three?', 'Chris', 'Sally', 'Clara', 'Insufficient information provided', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The given information only tells us that Chris is taller than Sally and Clara is shorter than Chris. However, we do not have any information about the height comparison between Chris and Clara. Therefore, it is impossible to determine who is the shortest among the three. The answer is Option D.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1638, 'Annie wants to buy a laptop that costs $1,200. She has saved $800 and plans to save $100 per month to reach her goal. How many months will it take for Annie to save enough money to buy the laptop?', '4 months', '6 months', '8 months', '10 months', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Annie needs to save $1,200 - $800 = $400. Since she saves $100 per month, the number of months required is $400 / $100 = 4 months. Therefore, it will take Annie 4 months to save enough money to buy the laptop.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1639, 'Bill can read 90 pages of a book in 2 hours. How long would it take him to read 150 pages?', '3 hours', '4 hours', '5 hours', '6 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Since Bill can read 90 pages in 2 hours, we can set up a proportion: 90 pages / 2 hours = 150 pages / x hours. Solving for x, we find that x = 5 hours. Therefore, it would take Bill 5 hours to read 150 pages.', 113, NULL, 0, 1),
(1827, 'In a recent study at XYZ College, it was found that 75% of students who participated in a mindfulness workshop reported reduced stress levels. Therefore, participating in the workshop will guarantee a reduction in stress for all college students.', 'Assuming that all college students are equally susceptible to stress', 'Assuming that the mindfulness workshop is the only factor that can reduce stress', 'Assuming that the 75% of students who reported reduced stress represent the entire student population', 'Assuming that stress levels can only be reduced through workshops and not through individual efforts', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The mistake in the reasoning is assuming that the 75% of students who reported reduced stress represent the entire student population. There may be other factors that contributed to their stress reduction, and the impact of the workshop may vary for different individuals.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1828, 'Stella and Myra are discussing different thinking styles for problem-solving. Stella believes that logical thinking is the best approach, while Myra argues that intuitive thinking is more effective. Which of the following, if true, weakens Myra\'s argument?', 'Several studies have shown that logical thinking leads to more accurate problem-solving outcomes.', 'Intuitive thinking relies heavily on gut feelings and personal biases, which can hinder objective decision-making.', 'Stella has successfully used intuitive thinking in the past to solve complex problems.', 'Myra has never personally experienced the benefits of logical thinking in problem-solving situations.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To weaken Myra\'s argument that intuitive thinking is more effective for problem-solving, we need a statement that contradicts or provides evidence against the effectiveness of intuitive thinking. If it is true that several studies have shown that logical thinking leads to more accurate problem-solving outcomes, then this weakens the argument for intuitive thinking as the preferred approach.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1829, 'During a college workshop on critical thinking, the facilitator described the steps for problem-solving as follows: identifying the problem, generating potential solutions, evaluating the options, making a decision, and implementing the chosen solution. Which of the following shows the correct order of these steps?', 'Identifying the problem, generating potential solutions, evaluating the options, making a decision, implementing the chosen solution', 'Implementing the chosen solution, making a decision, generating potential solutions, evaluating the options, identifying the problem', 'Generating potential solutions, evaluating the options, identifying the problem, making a decision, implementing the chosen solution', 'Evaluating the options, generating potential solutions, implementing the chosen solution, making a decision, identifying the problem', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The correct order of the problem-solving steps is: identifying the problem, generating potential solutions, evaluating the options, making a decision, and implementing the chosen solution. Option A is the only one that follows this order.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1830, 'Amelia can solve a math problem in 5 minutes. If she solved the problem 4 times, how long did it take her in total?', '10 minutes', '15 minutes', '20 minutes', '25 minutes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Since Amelia can solve the problem in 5 minutes, solving it 4 times would take 5 minutes x 4 = 20 minutes. Therefore, the answer is Option C.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1831, 'In a debate competition with 6 participants, Bobby finished second. Natasha finished before Daisy. Bobby finished before Daisy. Natasha was not first. Which one of the following statements cannot be true?', 'Daisy finished first', 'Natasha finished after Bobby', 'Bobby finished after Natasha', 'Daisy finished ahead of Bobby', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Natasha finished before Daisy. Bobby finished before Daisy. Therefore, the only possible order of finishing is: Daisy, Bobby, Natasha. Thus, Natasha cannot finish after Bobby.', 125, NULL, 0, 1);
INSERT INTO `question` (`id`, `question`, `option_1`, `option_2`, `option_3`, `option_4`, `option_5`, `option_6`, `option_7`, `option_8`, `correct_option`, `explanation`, `tst_id`, `marks`, `nvq`, `status`) VALUES
(1832, 'Sarah and Zoya are participating in a thinking competition. In the first round, each of them is given a set of numbers and they have to arrange them in a pattern. Sarah arranges the numbers in ascending order, starting from the smallest number, while Zoya arranges them in descending order, starting from the largest number. If Sarah\'s pattern starts with the number 3 and Zoya\'s pattern starts with the number 20, what is the largest number in Zoya\'s pattern?', '17', '18', '19', '21', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Sarah\'s pattern starts with the number 3, therefore Zoya\'s pattern starts with the largest number, which is 20. Since Zoya arranges the numbers in descending order, the next number in her pattern will be 19. Hence, the largest number in Zoya\'s pattern is 19.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1833, 'Adam and Bill are discussing the impact of critical thinking in decision-making. Adam believes that critical thinking helps individuals make better informed and rational choices, while Bill argues that intuition is more effective for quick decision-making. Which of the following, if true, weakens Bill\'s argument?', 'Critical thinking involves evaluating evidence, considering multiple perspectives, and reducing biases.', 'Intuition is often based on personal biases, emotions, or limited information, leading to biased decisions.', 'Adam has successfully utilized critical thinking in various decision-making scenarios.', 'Bill has relied solely on intuition in his decision-making process and achieved favorable outcomes.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To weaken Bill\'s argument that intuition is more effective for quick decision-making, we need a statement that contradicts or provides evidence against the effectiveness of intuition. If it is true that critical thinking involves evaluating evidence, considering multiple perspectives, and reducing biases, then this weakens the argument for intuition as the preferred approach for quick decision-making.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1834, 'Annie and Natasha both have to solve a puzzle. Annie can solve the puzzle in 4 hours, while Natasha can solve it in 6 hours. How long will it take for Annie and Natasha to solve the puzzle together?', '1.5 hours', '2 hours', '2.5 hours', '3 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Annie\'s rate of solving the puzzle is 1/4 per hour, while Natasha\'s rate is 1/6 per hour. When they work together, their combined rate is (1/4) + (1/6) = 5/12 per hour. The time it will take to solve the puzzle together is the reciprocal of their combined rate, which is 12/5 hours or 2.4 hours. Rounded to the nearest half hour, the answer is 2.5 hours.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1835, 'Oliver is working on a math problem. If he solved the problem correctly, it would take him 2 hours. However, Oliver made a mistake and it actually took him 3 hours. If Oliver\'s actual answer was 36, what would his answer have been if he solved the problem correctly?', '24', '28', '32', '40', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'If Oliver solved the problem correctly in 2 hours, his work speed would be 36 / 2 = 18 units per hour. Since it actually took him 3 hours, his actual work speed is 36 / 3 = 12 units per hour. Therefore, if he solved the problem correctly, his answer would have been 18 units per hour x 2 hours = 36.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1836, 'Stella is trying to decide which college major to choose. She is torn between studying psychology and computer science. Which of the following, if true, would strengthen the argument for Stella to choose computer science?', 'There is a high demand for computer science professionals, and job prospects are favorable.', 'Psychology offers a wider range of career opportunities compared to computer science.', 'Stella\'s close friend, who is currently studying computer science, highly recommends the program.', 'Stella performed exceptionally well in her high school psychology class.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To strengthen the argument for Stella to choose computer science, we need a statement that provides a favorable outlook for the field. If it is true that there is a high demand for computer science professionals and job prospects are favorable, then this strengthens the argument as it highlights the potential career opportunities in the field.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1837, 'Adam is organizing a group project for his college class. He assigns the tasks to his team members based on their individual strengths and skills. Which of the following, if true, strengthens the argument that Adam\'s approach to task assignment is effective?', 'Bill, who has excellent research skills, is assigned to gather information for the project.', 'Stella, who is good at problem-solving, is given the task of analyzing the data collected.', 'Myra, who has poor communication skills, is given the responsibility of presenting the findings to the class.', 'Adam chooses the tasks randomly without considering the strengths and skills of his team members.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To strengthen the argument that Adam\'s approach to task assignment is effective, we need a statement that reinforces the idea that tasks are assigned based on individual strengths and skills. If it is true that Bill, who has excellent research skills, is assigned to gather information for the project, then this most strengthens the argument as it demonstrates Adam\'s consideration of his team members\' abilities.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1838, 'Austin is studying for a history test. He estimates that he can memorize 10 key dates in 30 minutes. If Austin has 1.5 hours to study, how many key dates can he memorize?', '20', '25', '30', '35', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Austin can memorize 10 key dates in 30 minutes, which means he can memorize 10 / 30 = 1/3 key dates per minute. In 1.5 hours, there are 1.5 x 60 = 90 minutes. Therefore, Austin can memorize 1/3 x 90 = 30 key dates.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1839, 'Nathan rolled a fair six-sided die twice. What is the probability that the sum of the two numbers rolled is greater than 9?', '1/12', '1/9', '1/6', '1/3', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'To find the probability, we need to calculate the number of favorable outcomes and divide it by the total number of possible outcomes. The favorable outcomes are (4,6), (5,5), (5,6), and (6,4), for a total of 4. The total number of possible outcomes is 6 x 6 = 36. Therefore, the probability is 4/36 = 1/6.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1840, 'A group of friends compared their ages. Jenson is older than Sally. Georgia is older than Jenson. Who is the youngest in the group?', 'Jenson', 'Sally', 'Georgia', 'Cannot be determined', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The given information is not sufficient to determine who is the youngest in the group, as the relationship between Georgia and Sally is not specified.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1841, 'Bill and Adam are discussing the concept of lateral thinking. Bill argues that lateral thinking is more focused on generating creative ideas, while Adam believes it is primarily about finding unconventional solutions to problems. Which of the following, if true, supports Adam\'s viewpoint?', 'Lateral thinking involves breaking traditional thought patterns and considering multiple perspectives.', 'Bill is known for his artistic skills and often comes up with imaginative ideas through lateral thinking.', 'Adam has successfully used lateral thinking to find unique solutions to complex business challenges.', 'Lateral thinking is a systematic approach that follows predefined steps to generate innovative ideas.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To support Adam\'s viewpoint that lateral thinking is primarily about finding unconventional solutions to problems, we need a statement that aligns with his description of lateral thinking. If it is true that lateral thinking involves breaking traditional thought patterns and considering multiple perspectives, then this supports the idea that lateral thinking is focused on finding unconventional solutions rather than solely generating creative ideas.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1842, 'Alia and Marry are collaborating on a project. Alia can complete the project in 8 days working alone, while Marry can complete it in 12 days working alone. If they work together on the project, how many days will it take them to complete it?', '4', '5', '6', '7', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Alia can complete the project in 8 days, which means her work rate is 1/8 of the project per day. Marry can complete the project in 12 days, which means her work rate is 1/12 of the project per day. When they work together, their combined work rate is 1/8 + 1/12 = 5/24 of the project per day. Therefore, it will take them 24/5 = 4.8 days to complete the project, which rounds up to 5 days.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1843, 'A study found that students who study for 8 hours a day tend to get higher grades than those who study for only 2 hours a day. Bobby: I studied for 3 hours today, so I am guaranteed to get good grades tomorrow. Which of the following shows the mistake in Bobby\'s reasoning?', 'Bobby may not have studied enough to get good grades tomorrow.', 'Bobby does not know the grades of other students in his class.', 'Bobby is smarter than the rest of the students in his class.', 'Bobby may not be able to get good grades despite studying for 3 hours.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Bobby: I studied for 3 hours today, so I am guaranteed to get good grades tomorrow.\nThe study only indicates that students who study for 8 hours a day tend to get higher grades. It does not guarantee that those who study for less time will not get good grades. Therefore, the answer is Option D.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1844, 'In order to qualify for a scholarship, a student needs to have a GPA of 3.5 or higher and score above 1500 in the SAT. Chris has a GPA of 3.8 but scored 1450 in the SAT. Does Chris qualify for the scholarship?', 'Yes', 'No', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'No, Chris does not qualify for the scholarship because even though he has a GPA of 3.8 which is above the requirement, his SAT score is below the required minimum of 1500.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1845, 'Louis is taller than John, but not as tall as Jessie. Zoya is taller than John but not as tall as Louis. Who is the tallest among them?', 'Louis', 'John', 'Jessie', 'Zoya', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Since Louis is taller than John and Jessie is taller than Louis, it can be concluded that Jessie is the tallest.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1846, 'Bobby, Lloyd, Myra, and Amelia are all competing in a chess tournament. Whoever wins the most games wins the tournament. Bobby wins more games than Myra but fewer games than Amelia. Lloyd wins fewer games than Bobby. Who wins the tournament?', 'Amelia', 'Bobby', 'Myra', 'Lloyd', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Bobby wins more games than Myra but fewer games than Amelia. Lloyd wins fewer games than Bobby. Therefore, the order is Amelia, Bobby, Lloyd, Myra. Therefore, the answer is Option A.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1847, 'Sally, Lloyd, and Zoya are all studying different subjects: Math, English, and Science. Sally studies Math and English, while Lloyd studies English and Science. What subject does Zoya study that neither Sally nor Lloyd study?', 'Math', 'English', 'Science', 'None of the above', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Sally studies Math and English. Lloyd studies English and Science. Therefore, Zoya must study the subject that is left, which is Science. Therefore, the answer is Option C.', 125, NULL, 0, 1),
(1848, 'James is a businessman. He bought a few boxes of apples for $500. If an increase of 20% in the price of apples means he can buy 5 boxes less for the same amount of money, how many boxes did James buy originally?', '15 boxes', '20 boxes', '25 boxes', '30 boxes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'If the price of apples increase by 20%, James can get 1/6 less boxes. Therefore, the number of boxes he bought originally was 6/5 * 5 (which he can afford now), which equals 6 boxes. So, James originally bought 25 boxes.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1849, 'Henry bought 5 jars and 3 bags. The total cost of jars and bags was $160. If the price of a bag is 20% less than the price of a jar, what is the price of a jar?', '$20', '$24', '$30', '$36', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Let us suppose the price of a jar is x. Then, the price of a bag is 0.8x. Thus, 5x + 3*0.8x = 160. Solving for x, we get x = $24.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1850, 'Carl, a car salesman, earns a standard salary of $1000 per month. Besides, he receives 5% commission on all sales he makes. If in a particular month, his overall income was $2000, what was the worth of cars he sold that month?', '$10000', '$15000', '$20000', '$25000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The amount over Carl’s stationary salary represents his commission (2000 - 1000 = $1000). Since this amount was 5% of his sales, then the total worth of cars he sold was ($1000 / 5) * 100 = $20000.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1851, 'Lucy baked 100 cookies. She ate 20% of them and gave 25% of the remaining cookies to her friend. How many cookies does she have left?', '60 cookies', '40 cookies', '30 cookies', '70 cookies', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Lucy ate 20/100 * 100 = 20 cookies. So, she had 100 - 20 = 80 cookies left. Then she gave away 25/100 * 80 = 20 cookies. Therefore, Lucy has 80 - 20 = 60 cookies left.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1852, 'Clara bought a nice jacket for $300. Unfortunately, it went on sale the next week and was discounted by 20%. How much money could Clara have saved if she had waited for the sale?', '$20', '$40', '$60', '$80', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The discount Clara could have gotten is 20% of $300, which is 20/100 * $300 = $60.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1853, 'Peter is planning a birthday party and wants to order pizza. One pizza serves 8 people and costs $16. If Peter invite 30 friends, and wants everyone to have at least 2 servings, what will be the cost adjusting for a 10% service charge?', '$96', '$106', '$88', '$106', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Peter needs 30 friends * 2 servings = 60 servings. That\'s 60 servings / 8 servings per pizza = 7.5 pizzas, round up to 8 pizzas. The cost is 8 pizzas * $16/pizza = $128. Adding the 10% service charge, the total becomes $128 + ($128*10/100) = $140.80', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1854, 'Dennis is a clockmaker, he takes 4 hours to make a single clock. If he improve his efficiency and reduces the making time by 20%, how many clocks can he make in 10 days working 8 hours each day?', '20 clocks', '25 clocks', '30 clocks', '35 clocks', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The new time to make a clock is 80% of 4 hours which is 3.2 hours. In one day Dennis works for 8 hours, therefore he can make 8/3.2= 2.5 Clocks/day. Therefore in 10 days he can make 2.5*10= 25 clocks.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1855, 'Eliza’s salary was reduced by 15% after a company\'s budget cut. If new salary is $2550, what was her original salary?', '$2850', '$3000', '$2450', '$3400', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Eliza’s reduced salary represents 100% - 15% = 85% of her original salary. So if 85% of her original salary equals $2550, 1% equals $2550 / 85 = $30. Hence, her original salary was $30 x 100 = $3000.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1856, 'Emma bought a set of books for $50. After reading them, she sold the books to a secondhand store. The store bought them for 40% less than the original price. How much did Emma get for the books?', '$20', '$30', '$25', '$35', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Emma sold the books for $50 - 40% of $50 = $50 - $20 = $30.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1857, 'John is a business man who recently imported 2000 glasses. However, during transportation, 5% of glasses broke. John was able to sell 85% of the remaining glasses. How many glasses does he have left?', '100 glasses', '140 glasses', '180 glasses', '220 glasses', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'John lost 5/100 * 2000 = 100 glasses in transit. So, he had 2000 - 100 = 1900 glasses left. He then sold 85/100 * 1900 = 1615 glasses. Therefore, John has 1900 - 1615 = 285 glasses left.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1858, 'If a car depreciates yearly by 15% of its value at the beginning of the year, what will be the price of the car after a year if its initial cost was $25000?', '$22000', '$21250', '$17760', '$18750', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The value of the car after a year would be $25000 - 15% of $25000 = $25000 - $3750 = $21250.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1859, 'Freda runs a bakery. One day she baked 360 cupcakes. 30% got sold before noon. From the remaining cupcakes, 50% got sold in the afternoon. How many cupcakes did Freda have left at the end of the day?', '126 cupcakes', '252 cupcakes', '300 cupcakes', '158 cupcakes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Freda sold 30/100 * 360 = 108 cupcakes before noon. So, she had 360 - 108 = 252 cupcakes left. Then she sold 50/100 * 252 = 126 cupcakes in the afternoon. Therefore, Freda has 252 - 126 = 126 cupcakes left.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1860, 'Henry works as a sales executive in a firm. If 5% of the cars he sells are electric cars and he has sold 3500 cars so far, how many electric cars has he sold?', '50 cars', '100 cars', '175 cars', '200 cars', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Henry has sold 5/100 * 3500 = 175 electric cars.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1861, 'Shane, a college student, saves 15% of his pocket money every month. If he receives $500 monthly, how much has he saved over the course of a year?', '$600', '$750', '$900', '$1200', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Each month Shane saves 15/100*$500 = $75. Therefore, in one year, he would have saved $75*12 = $900.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1862, 'Darcy bought a book for $80 and sold it at loss of 15%. What is the selling price of the book?', '$60', '$68', '$72', '$75', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The selling price of the book is $80 - 15% of $80 = $80 - $12 = $68.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1863, 'Kate is a teacher who just got a raise of 10%, which results in a new salary of $3850. How much was Kate\'s salary prior to the raise?', '$3200', '$3500', '$3600', '$4000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Kate\'s new salary is 110% of her old salary. Therefore her old salary was $3850 ÷ 1.1 = $3500.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1864, 'Nathan, a delivery man, is paid $1.20 for delivering a small packet and $2.40 for a large packet. In one day, if he delivers 60% large packets and 40% small packets of total 100 packets, what is his total earning for the day?', '$190', '$200', '$210', '$220', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Nathan delivers 60 large packets and 40 small packets. His earning is (60 * $2.4) + (40 * $1.2) = $144 + $48 = $192.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1865, 'Nora, a glasses maker, increased the price of her glasses by 15% for the holiday season and then decreased it by 15% after the holidays. If the original price was $50, what is the final price?', '$45', '$52', '$55', '$50', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'After the increase, the price was $50 * 1.15 = $57.5. after the decrease, the price was $57.5 * 0.85 = $48.87 approx $49.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1866, 'A shop is selling chocolates at $20 per box. If a customer buys more than 10 boxes, they will get a discount of 5% for all boxes. How much should a customer pay for 15 boxes?', '$280', '$290', '$300', '$310', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The price for 15 boxes without discount is 15 * $20 = $300. With a 5% discount the price becomes $300 - ($300 * 5/100) = $285.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1867, 'Jackson\'s monthly salary was $4000, but then he received a 10% increase. Some time later, his salary was decreased by 10%. What is his salary after these changes?', '$3960', '$4000', '$4050', '$4080', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The salary after the increase is $4000 + 10% of $4000 == $4400. Then the decrease is $4400 - 10% of $4400 = $3960.', 70, NULL, 0, 1),
(1868, 'Billy works at a company, which gives an allowance for parking spaces. They give $4 for every 3 meters. If Billy is given $64 for his car in a year, how many meters does his parking space span?', '48 meters', '52 meters', '36 meters', '60 meters', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To solve this question, we will use the concept of ratio. We\'ll first build the ratio of dollars to meters, which is 4:3. Then, translate this ratio in terms of Billy\'s situation - $64:X meters. Cross-multiply and solve for X, we get X = 48. Therefore, Billy\'s parking space spans 48 meters.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1869, 'Henry, a businessman, planned to ship his apples to Emma over three shipments. If the ratio of the number of apples in the first, second, and third shipment is 5:7:3, and the total number of apples he got is 2250, how many apples are there in the second shipment?', '750 apples', '1050 apples', '900 apples', '550 apples', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'First calculate the total units in the ratios which is 5+7+3=15. Each unit in the ratio is 2250/15=150 apples. Therefore, number of apples in the second shipment is 7(units) * 150 = 1050 apples.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1870, 'Alfred, a teacher, has a box of pencils for his 16 students. If he has 192 pencils and he wants to distribute them in such a way that each female student gets double the number of pencils as each male student, how many male and female students are in his class if the ratio of the number of female to male students is 4:3?', '8 males and 8 females', '9 males and 7 females', '7 males and 9 females', '6 males and 10 females', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Let number of pencils per male be x. Then, each female gets 2x pencils. Total pencils = male students * x + female students * 2x = 192. Also, total students = male students + female students = 16. Furthermore, we have the ratio of female to male students as 4:3. Solving these equations, we get 7 male students and 9 female students.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1871, 'James has been working as a factory worker for 12 years. His boss gave increments in the ratio of 1:2:4 in every four years. If his initial salary was $5000, what is his current salary?', '$20000', '$10000', '$15000', '$25000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Every four years, James got increments based on the ratio 1:2:4. In the first four-year period, he got a raise of 1*x. In the next 4-year period, the raise was 2*x, and in the last four-year period, the raise was 4*x. If we consider x as having the unit of $5000, which is his starting salary, then his current salary would be 5000+1*5000+2*5000+4*5000 = $20000.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1872, 'Clara is a pastry chef who uses chocolate and sugar in the ratio of 5:2 to make cakes. This month, she has made 2800g of cakes. How much chocolate did she use?', '2000g', '500g', '800g', '1000g', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The ratio of chocolate to sugar in the cakes is 5:2, so the total ratio is 5+2=7. Each unit of the ratio will correspond to 2800/7 = 400g of ingredients. Therefore, the amount of chocolate in the cakes is 5 units * 400g/unit = 2000g.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1873, 'Dennis, a book dealer, sells books at a ratio of 5:2:3 for fiction, non-fiction, and educational respectively. If he sold 1000 books last month, how many non-fiction books did he sell?', '200 books', '250 books', '300 books', '350 books', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'First, calculate the total ratio units, which is 5+2+3=10. Each unit of the ratio corresponds to 1000/10 = 100 books. Therefore, the number of non-fiction books Dennis sold is 2 units * 100 books/unit = 200 books.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1874, 'Zoya and Katty are selling jackets to earn money. If the ratio of Zoya\'s to Katty\'s sales in June is 3:2, and Zoya earned $3600 in that month. How much did Katty earn?', '$1800', '$2400', '$1200', '$3000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The ratio of Zoya\'s to Katty\'s sales is 3:2. This means for every 3 units Zoya earns, Katty earns 2. Therefore, each unit is worth $1200 (i.e., $3600 / 3). So, Katty earned 2 units which is $2400.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1875, 'Bobby ordered a pizza to share with his roommates. If the ratio of the slices Bobby ate to the slices his roommates ate is 5:3 and they left 3 slices of the 16 slices they got, how many slices did Bobby eat?', '5 slices', '6 slices', '7 slices', '8 slices', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Firstly, you need to know that they ate 16 - 3 = 13 slices. The ratio of the slices Bobby ate to the slices his roommates ate is 5:3, so the total ratio is 5+3=8. Each unit of the ratio corresponds to 13/8 = 1.625 slices. Therefore, Bobby ate 5 units * 1.625 slices/unit = 8.125 slices. Since Bobby can\'t eat a fraction of a slice, we round down to the nearest whole number, 8 slices.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1876, 'A train contains cars for passengers and merchandise at a ratio of 3:2. If it has 30 cars, how many of them are passenger cars?', '18 cars', '12 cars', '15 cars', '20 cars', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The total ratio units are 3(passenger cars) + 2(merchandise cars) = 5. Each unit of the ratio corresponds to 30/5 = 6 cars. Therefore, there are 3 units * 6 cars/unit = 18 passenger cars.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1877, 'Lucy bought jars of pens for her office employees. Each jar contains 15 pens, and the ratio of black to blue pens is 4:1. If Lucy bought 900 pens, how many black pens are there?', '600 pens', '720 pens', '480 pens', '300 pens', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Each jar has 15 pens and Lucy bought 900 pens, which means Lucy bought 900/15=60 jars. As for the color distribution, there is a total of 5 units (4 units of black and 1 unit of blue). Each unit represents 60/5=12 jars. Therefore, the number of black pens is 12 jars/unit * 4 units * 15 pens/jar = 720 pens.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1878, 'A ship\'s crew consists of officers and sailors at the ratio of 2:5. If the total number of crew members is 210, how many sailors are there?', '60 sailors', '150 sailors', '70 sailors', '80 sailors', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Let us first determine the total units, which sum up to 2+5=7. Now, let\'s calculate the number assigned to each unit. It will be 210/7=30. Therefore, the number of sailors will be 5 (units) * 30 = 150 sailors.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1879, 'John works at a factory and earns $5000 per month. His savings, expenses, and taxes are in the ratio of 4:3:1. How much does John save every month?', '$2000', '$3000', '$2500', '$1500', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'First, calculate the total ratio units, which is 4+3+1=8. Each unit of the ratio corresponds to 5000/8 = $625. Therefore, John saves 4 units * $625/unit = $2500 per month.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1880, 'Two motor companies produced cars in the ratio 2:3. If the combined total cars produced were 200 and the difference of the cars produced was 20, how many cars did the first company produce?', '80 cars', '90 cars', '70 cars', '100 cars', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The difference between the two ratios is 3(Second Company) - 2(First Company) = 1. This difference corresponds to the given difference of cars produced, 20 cars. Following the ratio gives us - First Company\'s production = 2 * 20 = 40. The total cars produced by both is given as 200, therefore, the first company produced = 200 - 40 = 90 cars.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1881, 'Carl has different types of fruit trees in his back yard. The trees are apple trees, peach trees, and orange trees. The ratio of apple trees to the peach trees is 2:3, and the ratio of peach trees to orange trees is 4:2. If Carl has 35 trees in total, how many peach trees does he have?', '20 trees', '10 trees', '15 trees', '12 trees', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'From the first ratio, the amount of apple trees is 2/3 the amount of peach trees, so let p be the number of peach trees, and 2/3 * p is the number of apple trees. From the second ratio, the number of peach trees is 4/2 twice the number of orange trees, so p/2 is the number of orange trees. The total number of trees is 35 = 2/3*p + p + p/2 = 7/6*p. Solving this equation gives us p = 30, therefore, Carl has 12 peach trees.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1882, 'Luke and Peter are two business partners who have decided to split their profit according to the ratio of their investment, which is 3:2 respectively. If their total profit for the fiscal year was $8500, how much profit did Peter get?', '$3250', '$3000', '$3500', '$5250', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'First, find total parts of the ratio which is 3(Luke)+2(Peter)=5. Then one part of the ratio is $8500/5=$1700. Hence, Peter\'s share is 2*1700 = $3400.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1883, 'A girl has pens and pencils in the ratio 3:2. If she has 20 pens, how many pencils does she have?', '10 pencils', '15 pencils', '20 pencils', '13 pencils', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'If the ratio of pens to pencils is 3:2, then each \'part\' of pens corresponds to 20/3 = 6.67 pens. Therefore, the number of pencils is 2 parts * 6.67 = approx. 13.33 pencils. As she can\'t have a fraction of a pencil, the closest whole number that satisfies the ratio is 20 pencils.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1884, 'In a park, the ratio of men to women is 3:5. If there are 24 men in the park, how many women are there?', '30 women', '40 women', '20 women', '10 women', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Firstly, figure out the value of the ratio\'s \'part\', which is 24/3=8. Therefore, the number of women is 5 parts * 8 = 40 women.', 126, NULL, 0, 1),
(1905, 'The passage below is true? \n \n3. Jim is a college student studying engineering. He always gets good grades on his exams. \n \nIf the quoted passage above is true, which of the following statements is true?', 'If Sally is a college student studying engineering, she always gets good grades on her exams.', 'If Bill is not a college student studying engineering, he does not get good grades on his exams.', 'If Lloyd is a college student studying engineering, he always gets good grades on his exams.', 'If Alia is not a college student studying engineering, she does not get good grades on her exams.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The correct answer is (b) \'If Bill is not a college student studying engineering, he does not get good grades on his exams.\' This follows directly from the given passage, stating that Jim, a college student studying engineering, always gets good grades on his exams.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1906, 'The passage below is true? \n \n4. All students who actively participate in class discussions have higher grades. \n \nIf the quoted passage above is true, which of the following statements is true?', 'If Sally has high grades, she actively participates in class discussions.', 'If Bill does not actively participate in class discussions, he has low grades.', 'If Lloyd actively participates in class discussions, he has low grades.', 'If Alia has low grades, she actively participates in class discussions.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The correct answer is (a) \'If Sally has high grades, she actively participates in class discussions.\' This follows directly from the given passage, stating that all students who actively participate in class discussions have higher grades.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1907, 'Daisy has to finish a 600-page book for her English literature class. If she reads 40 pages every day, how many days will it take her to finish the book?', '12 days', '15 days', '18 days', '20 days', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The correct answer is (c) \'18 days.\' To find the number of days, divide the total number of pages (600) by the number of pages read per day (40).', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1908, 'John plans to save money for a new laptop. He sets a goal to save $1200 within 9 months. If he saves the same amount of money each month, how much should he save per month?', '$100', '$150', '$200', '$250', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The correct answer is (a) \'$100.\' To find the amount to save per month, divide the total amount to save ($1200) by the number of months (9).', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1909, 'Lucy has recently started a clothing business. Which of the following outcomes is not possible?', 'Lucy bought trendy clothes from a designer but had low demand for her accessories.', 'Lucy didn\'t buy trendy clothes from a designer but had high demand for her accessories.', 'Lucy sold a lot of trendy clothes and had high demand for her accessories.', 'Lucy bought trendy clothes from a designer and had high demand for her accessories.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The correct answer is (b) \'Lucy didn\'t buy trendy clothes from a designer but had high demand for her accessories.\' According to the given conditions, Lucy can only have high demand for her accessories if she buys trendy clothes from a designer.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1910, 'James is a college student who is preparing for two exams: Math and Science. If he studies for 5 hours for Math and 4 hours for Science, the probability of passing both exams is 0.6, and the probability of passing at least one exam is 0.8. What is the probability of James passing only the Science exam?', '0.2', '0.3', '0.4', '0.5', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Explanation needs to be generated.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1911, 'John scored 90% on his math test. If all students who score above 80% receive a certificate of achievement, will John receive a certificate?', 'No, because he did not score above 80%.', 'Yes, because he scored above 80%.', 'No, because the question does not provide enough information to determine if John will receive a certificate.', 'Yes, because he scored 90%.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The correct answer is (b) \"Yes, because he scored above 80%.\" The question states that all students who score above 80% receive a certificate of achievement, and John scored 90%, which is above 80%. Therefore, he will receive a certificate.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1912, 'Flora is studying for a history exam. She has 100 pages of reading to complete, and she has already read 60% of the pages. How many more pages does Flora need to read to complete her reading?', '40', '60', '10', '50', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The correct answer is (d) \"50.\" If Flora has read 60% of the 100 pages, that means she has read 0.60 * 100 = 60 pages. To find out how many more pages she needs to read to complete her reading, we subtract the number of pages she has already read from the total number of pages: 100 - 60 = 40. Therefore, Flora needs to read 50 more pages to complete her reading.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1913, 'A math test has three sections: algebra, geometry, and statistics. The algebra section is worth twice as much as the geometry section, and the statistics section is worth half as much as the algebra section. If Tom scored 80% on the algebra section, 90% on the geometry section, and 85% on the statistics section, what is Tom\'s overall score in the test?', '82%', '83%', '84%', '86%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'To find Tom\'s overall score, we need to calculate the weighted average of his scores. The algebra section is worth 2/5 of the total score, the geometry section is worth 1/5, and the statistics section is worth 1/10. Therefore, Tom\'s overall score is (80% * (2/5)) + (90% * (1/5)) + (85% * (1/10)) = 84%.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1914, 'Sarah, Lucy, and Adam are solving a logic puzzle. During the discussion, they make the following statements:\n\nSarah: If the blue ball is in box 1, then the red ball is in box 2.\nLucy: If the red ball is in box 3, then the green ball is in box 4.\nAdam: If the yellow ball is in box 5, then the blue ball is in box 1.\n\nWhat can be concluded about the location of the balls?', 'The green ball is in box 4.', 'The blue ball is in box 1.', 'The red ball is in box 2.', 'The yellow ball is in box 5.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Based on Sarah\'s statement, if the blue ball is in box 1, the red ball is in box 2. Then, according to Adam\'s statement, if the yellow ball is in box 5, the blue ball is in box 1. Combining these two statements, if the yellow ball is in box 5, the red ball must be in box 2. Therefore, the conclusion that can be drawn is that the yellow ball is in box 5.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1915, 'In a college class of 40 students, there are 15 students who are majoring in mathematics. If 20% of the students who are majoring in mathematics are male and the rest are female, how many female students are majoring in mathematics?', '8', '9', '10', '11', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'If 20% of the students majoring in mathematics are male, then 80% of them are female. Therefore, the number of female students majoring in mathematics is 0.8 * 15 = 12.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1916, 'A college library has a collection of 5000 books. If 60% of the books are non-fiction and the rest are fiction, how many fiction books are in the library?', '2000', '2500', '3000', '3500', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'If 60% of the books are non-fiction, then 40% of them are fiction. Therefore, the number of fiction books in the library is 0.4 * 5000 = 2000.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1917, 'Chris, Sarah, Evan, and Jessie are taking a math test. Chris and Sarah both scored 90% on the test, while Evan scored 80% and Jessie scored 85%. What is the average score of Chris, Sarah, Evan, and Jessie?', '87.5%', '84.5%', '86%', '88%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'To find the average score, add up all the scores and then divide by the number of scores. (90+90+80+85)/4 = 86. Therefore, the answer is Option C.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1918, 'Chris, Sarah, Evan, and Jessie are training for a marathon. Chris can run 9 miles in 1 hour, Sarah can run 7 miles in 1 hour, Evan can run 8 miles in 1 hour, and Jessie can run 6 miles in 1 hour. If they all start running at the same time and maintain their pace, who will finish the marathon first?', 'Chris', 'Sarah', 'Evan', 'Jessie', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Since Chris can run the highest number of miles in 1 hour, he will finish the marathon first. Therefore, the answer is Option A.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1919, 'In a game of Monopoly, Sally started with $1500. After playing for 5 rounds, she had a total of $1325. What was her average earnings per round?', '$175', '$135', '$155', '$185', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'To find the average earnings per round, divide the total earnings ($1325) by the number of rounds (5). $1325 / 5 = $265. Therefore, Sally\'s average earnings per round was $135. The correct answer is Option B.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1920, 'Austin is organizing a fundraiser for his college. He plans to sell tickets for $20 each. If his goal is to raise $5000, how many tickets does he need to sell?', '250', '300', '350', '400', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'To find the number of tickets Austin needs to sell, divide the total amount he wants to raise ($5000) by the price per ticket ($20). $5000 / $20 = 250. Therefore, Austin needs to sell 250 tickets. The correct answer is Option C.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1921, 'Bobby is twice as old as Nathan. If Bobby is 20 years old, how old is Nathan?', '15', '10', '5', '2.5', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'If Bobby is 20 years old and twice as old as Nathan, then Nathan must be half of Bobby\'s age. Therefore, Nathan is 10 years old.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1922, 'Flora and Daisy are running a race of 100 meters. Flora runs at a speed of 10 meters per second, while Daisy runs at a speed of 15 meters per second. How many seconds will it take for Daisy to finish the race?', '4', '6', '8', '10', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'If Daisy runs at a speed of 15 meters per second and the race distance is 100 meters, then she will finish the race in 100/15 = 6.67 seconds. Since we need to consider a whole number of seconds, it will take Daisy 7 seconds to finish the race.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1923, 'Dennis and Philips are competing in a track race. If Dennis can run 100 meters in 10 seconds and Philips can run 100 meters in 12 seconds, which of the following statements is true?', 'Dennis is faster than Philips.', 'Phillips is faster than Dennis.', 'Dennis and Philips run at the same speed.', 'There is not enough information to determine the outcome.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Because we know that Dennis can run 100 meters in 10 seconds and Philips can run 100 meters in 12 seconds, we can conclude that Dennis is faster than Philips. Therefore, the answer is Option A.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1924, 'Zoya and Amelia are solving a math problem. Zoya can solve the problem in 20 minutes, while Amelia can solve the problem in 15 minutes. Who will finish solving the problem first if they start at the same time?', 'Zoya', 'Amelia', 'Both will finish at the same time', 'There is not enough information to determine the outcome.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Because we know that Zoya can solve the problem in 20 minutes and Amelia can solve the problem in 15 minutes, we can conclude that Amelia will finish solving the problem first. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1925, 'Louis has to complete 5 tasks for his college project. Task A takes 40 minutes, Task B takes 25 minutes, Task C takes 50 minutes, Task D takes 30 minutes, and Task E takes 15 minutes. If Louis starts working on his project at 9:00 am, what time will he finish all the tasks?', '11:00 am', '10:55 am', '10:45 am', '10:30 am', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'To calculate the total time it takes for Louis to complete all the tasks, we add the time for each task: 40 + 25 + 50 + 30 + 15 = 160 minutes. As each task is completed one by one, Louis will finish all the tasks 160 minutes after he starts. Therefore, he will finish at 9:00 am + 160 minutes = 10:40 am. Since we need to find the time when Louis finishes all the tasks, the answer is 10:55 am.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1926, 'Alia needs to finish reading a book for her literature class. The book has 350 pages, and she reads at an average speed of 45 pages per hour. If Alia starts reading the book at 3:00 pm, what time will she finish reading the book?', '8:00 pm', '6:30 pm', '9:30 pm', '7:45 pm', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To calculate the total time it takes for Alia to finish reading the book, we divide the number of pages by her reading speed: 350 pages / 45 pages/hour = 7.78 hours. Since Alia is starting at 3:00 pm, she will finish reading the book 7.78 hours later. Therefore, she will finish at 10:48 pm + 7.78 hours = 6:48 pm. However, we need to round up to the nearest hour, so the answer is 7:00 pm.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1927, 'James is studying for an exam. If James studies for at least 4 hours every day, then he will pass the exam. Otherwise, he will fail. If James passes the exam, he will celebrate by going out with his friends. Which one of the following outcomes is not possible?', 'James studied for 3 hours and passed the exam.', 'James studied for 5 hours and failed the exam.', 'James studied for 4 hours and passed the exam.', 'James studied for 6 hours and passed the exam.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'If James studied for 5 hours, he would pass the exam according to the given conditions.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1928, 'Natasha loves to bake cookies. If Natasha bakes at least 100 cookies, then she will have enough to share with her friends. Otherwise, she will not. Natasha can only bake at least 100 cookies if she has enough ingredients. For Natasha to have enough ingredients, she must buy at least 5 pounds of flour. Which one of the following outcomes is not possible?', 'Natasha baked 80 cookies and had enough to share with her friends.', 'Natasha bought 3 pounds of flour and baked at least 100 cookies.', 'Natasha baked 120 cookies, which meant she had enough to share with her friends.', 'Natasha bought 6 pounds of flour and baked at least 100 cookies.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'If Natasha only bought 3 pounds of flour, she would not be able to bake at least 100 cookies according to the given conditions.', 128, NULL, 0, 1),
(1929, 'Bobby is investing in a stock. He bought 100 shares of a company\'s stock at $50 per share. The value of the stock increased by 10% over the next year. How much profit did Bobby make if he sold all his shares at the increased price?', '$500', '$1000', '$1500', '$2000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The value of each stock increased by 10%, which is $50 * 0.1 = $5. So, the increased price per share is $50 + $5 = $55. Bobby sold 100 shares at $55 per share, so his total earnings were 100 * $55 = $5500. Bobby initially invested 100 * $50 = $5000. Therefore, Bobby made a profit of $5500 - $5000 = $500.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1930, 'Alex believes that if he memorizes all the formulas for his math exam, he will get a perfect score. Which of the following is a mistake in Alex\'s reasoning?', 'Memorizing formulas does not guarantee a perfect score on the exam', 'Alex is already a math genius, so he doesn\'t need to study at all', 'The math exam will only consist of questions that require formulaic solutions', 'Alex should focus on other subjects instead of spending time memorizing formulas', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The mistake that Alex has made in his reasoning is assuming that memorizing formulas will automatically result in a perfect score on the math exam. This may not be the case as the exam may include conceptual questions that require more than just formulaic knowledge.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1931, 'David is a college student preparing for a Selective-Set-Express aptitude exam. He wants to improve his reading speed. He decides to read a book with a total of 300 pages. If he reads 50 pages each day, how many days will it take him to finish reading the book?', '4 days', '6 days', '8 days', '10 days', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'David reads 50 pages each day, so it will take him a total of 300 / 50 = 6 days to finish reading the book.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1932, 'In the field of competitive sports, athletes who undergo rigorous training programs tend to outperform those who rely solely on natural talent. Extensive training enhances skills, improves endurance, and boosts overall performance. Daisy: I am a naturally talented athlete, so I don\'t need to undergo any rigorous training program. Therefore, I will always outperform anyone.', 'Daisy might have the opportunity to further improve her skills and performance through rigorous training, even with natural talent.', 'Competitive sports teams often prioritize individual skills over teamwork and communication.', 'Athletes who rely on natural talent usually perform better than those who undergo extensive training.', 'Daisy assumes that natural talent alone guarantees superior performance without any need for training.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Daisy\'s mistake lies in assuming that her natural talent alone guarantees that she will always outperform others, without any need for training. Option D highlights this mistake, as it states that Daisy assumes natural talent alone guarantees superior performance without any need for training.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1933, 'Entering the field of computer programming requires proficiency in at least 2 programming languages and a strong understanding of algorithms and data structures. Most successful programmers also possess problem-solving skills and can work well in teams.', 'Liam: I am proficient in Java and Python, and I have a good grasp of algorithms and data structures. I enjoy solving problems and have experience working on group projects. I will definitely become a computer programmer.', 'Emma: I am familiar with a few programming languages and have a basic understanding of algorithms and data structures. Although I struggle with problem-solving and prefer to work alone, I still have a chance at becoming a computer programmer.', 'Liam: I am proficient in Java and Python, and I have a good grasp of algorithms and data structures. However, I struggle with problem-solving and often find it challenging to work in teams. I cannot become a computer programmer.', 'Emma: I am familiar with a few programming languages and have a basic understanding of algorithms and data structures. I also possess strong problem-solving skills and excel at collaborating with others. I will definitely become a computer programmer.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Emma\'s reasoning is correct. While she may not meet all of the requirements mentioned, the passage does not state that these requirements are absolute. Therefore, Emma still has a chance at becoming a computer programmer.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1934, 'Johnny wants to express his gratitude to his math teacher, Ms. Jones, for her dedication and support throughout the year. Which of the following, if true, would strengthen Johnny\'s argument for expressing his gratitude?', 'Ms. Jones has been teaching math for 10 years and has won multiple teaching awards.', 'Johnny struggled in math at the beginning of the year but improved significantly under Ms. Jones\' guidance.', 'Ms. Jones often stays after school to help struggling students with their math homework.', 'Johnny\'s classmates also appreciate Ms. Jones and have shared positive feedback about her teaching methods.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Option C strengthens Johnny\'s argument by highlighting Ms. Jones\' dedication and support. The fact that she often stays after school to help struggling students with their math homework demonstrates her commitment to her students, making her worthy of gratitude.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1935, 'Sarah is a college student who wants to improve her Selective-Set-Express skills. She decides to take a practice test consisting of 50 questions. She answers 40 questions correctly and 10 questions incorrectly. What is her percentage score on the practice test?', '80%', '85%', '90%', '95%', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Sarah answered 40 out of 50 questions correctly, so her percentage score is (40/50) * 100% = 80%. Therefore, her percentage score on the practice test is 80%.', 129, NULL, 0, 1);
INSERT INTO `question` (`id`, `question`, `option_1`, `option_2`, `option_3`, `option_4`, `option_5`, `option_6`, `option_7`, `option_8`, `correct_option`, `explanation`, `tst_id`, `marks`, `nvq`, `status`) VALUES
(1936, 'David is preparing for a Selective-Set-Express aptitude exam and wants to improve his chances of success. He decides to study for 6 hours a day for 4 days. If David completes 75% of his planned study time, how many hours did he actually study?', '12 hours', '16 hours', '18 hours', '24 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'David planned to study for 6 hours a day for 4 days, which gives a total of 6 x 4 = 24 hours. If he completes 75% of his planned study time, he actually studied 75/100 x 24 = 18 hours. Therefore, the answer is option C.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1937, 'A bakery sells chocolate chip cookies and oatmeal cookies. The chocolate chip cookies are packaged in boxes of 20, while the oatmeal cookies are packaged in boxes of 12. If Bobby wants to buy an equal number of chocolate chip and oatmeal cookies, what is the minimum number of boxes of each type that he needs to buy?', 'He needs to buy at least 8 boxes of chocolate chip cookies and 5 boxes of oatmeal cookies.', 'He needs to buy at least 10 boxes of chocolate chip cookies and 8 boxes of oatmeal cookies.', 'He needs to buy at least 12 boxes of chocolate chip cookies and 4 boxes of oatmeal cookies.', 'He needs to buy at least 6 boxes of chocolate chip cookies and 6 boxes of oatmeal cookies.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To find the minimum number of boxes of each type, we need to find the lowest common multiple of 20 and 12. The lowest common multiple of 20 and 12 is 60. Therefore, Bobby needs to buy at least 8 boxes of chocolate chip cookies (20 x 4 = 80 cookies) and 5 boxes of oatmeal cookies (12 x 5 = 60 cookies) to have an equal number of each type.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1938, 'Emily believes that if she studies for an extra hour every day, she will improve her test scores. Which of the following is a mistake in Emily\'s reasoning?', 'Studying for an extra hour every day does not guarantee improved test scores', 'Emily is already at the top of her class, so she doesn\'t need to study more', 'Spending more time studying will lead to increased fatigue and decreased test performance', 'Emily should focus on other areas of her life instead of studying', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The mistake that Emily has made in her reasoning is assuming that studying for an extra hour every day will automatically lead to improved test scores. This may not be the case as there are various factors that can affect test performance.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1939, 'Lucy wants to paint a room in her house. The room has an area of 150 square feet. A gallon of paint can cover 300 square feet. How many gallons of paint does Lucy need to buy?', '0.5 gallons', '1 gallon', '2 gallons', '3 gallons', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Lucy needs to cover an area of 150 square feet. Since a gallon of paint can cover 300 square feet, Lucy needs 150 / 300 = 0.5 gallons of paint. However, since you can\'t buy a fraction of a gallon, Lucy needs to buy at least 1 gallon of paint.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1940, 'For a person to qualify for a scholarship, they must either have a high GPA or be involved in extracurricular activities. If a person has both a high GPA and is involved in extracurricular activities, they are eligible for an academic excellence scholarship. Meredith has a high GPA but is not involved in any extracurricular activities. Can she still qualify for the academic excellence scholarship?', 'Yes', 'No', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'No. In order to qualify for the academic excellence scholarship, a person must have both a high GPA and be involved in extracurricular activities. Since Meredith is not involved in any extracurricular activities, she does not meet the eligibility criteria.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1941, 'Amelia is planning a road trip across a state that has a speed limit of 70 mph on highways. She wants to reach her destination, which is 420 miles away, in the shortest amount of time possible. What is the minimum amount of time it would take for Amelia to reach her destination if she maintains a constant speed of 70 mph?', 'She would reach her destination in 5 hours.', 'She would reach her destination in 6 hours.', 'She would reach her destination in 7 hours.', 'She would reach her destination in 8 hours.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To calculate the minimum amount of time it would take for Amelia to reach her destination, divide the total distance by the speed. 420 miles / 70 mph = 6 hours. Since Amelia wants to reach her destination in the shortest amount of time possible, she would maintain a constant speed of 70 mph and reach her destination in 5 hours (rounding down to the nearest whole number).', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1942, 'Mike has decided to only study for his biology exams on the weekends. He believes that this will give him enough time to prepare for all of his exams. Which of the following is a mistake in Mike\'s reasoning?', 'Studying only on weekends may not provide enough time to adequately prepare for all of his exams', 'Studying on weekends will automatically lead to academic success', 'All of his exams will require the same amount of preparation', 'Studying for biology exams is more important than studying for any other subject', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The mistake that Mike has made in his reasoning is assuming that studying only on weekends will give him enough time to prepare for all of his exams. This may not be the case as different exams may require different amounts of preparation.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1943, 'Nora is buying a new phone. The phone she wants to buy costs $400. She has a coupon that gives her a 20% discount on the phone. How much will Nora pay for the phone with the coupon?', '$280', '$320', '$360', '$400', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Nora will pay 100% - 20% = 80% of the original price. 80% of $400 is 0.8 * $400 = $320. Therefore, Nora will pay $320 for the phone with the coupon.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1944, 'Ruby wants to join a selective school for an advanced computer science program. The school has a limited number of seats available, and candidates are selected based on their performance in an aptitude exam. Ruby decides to practice solving advanced-level coding problems in preparation for the exam. If she solves 60% of the problems correctly, how many problems did she solve correctly if there were 100 problems in total?', '40 problems', '60 problems', '75 problems', '90 problems', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'If Ruby solved 60% of the problems correctly, she solved 60/100 x 100 = 60 problems correctly. Therefore, the answer is option C.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1945, 'The Green family has a tradition of hosting a summer barbecue every year. This summer, they are planning to invite 50 of their friends and family members to the barbecue. However, they have limited space in their backyard and can only accommodate a maximum of 40 people. If they decide to invite 50 people, they will need to rent a larger venue. On the other hand, if they limit the guest list to 40 people, they can host the barbecue in their backyard. \nNathan: The Green family can host the barbecue in their backyard and invite all 50 people. \nStella: If the Green family wants to invite all 50 people, they will need to rent a larger venue.', 'Nathan only', 'Stella only', 'Both Nathan and Stella', 'Neither Nathan nor Stella', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Stella is correct. According to the given information, if the Green family wants to invite all 50 people, they will need to rent a larger venue as they have limited space in their backyard. Therefore, Stella\'s statement aligns with the provided conditions.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1946, 'Tom runs faster than Harry, but slower than Peter.', 'Tom is the fastest runner in the world.', 'Harry is the slowest runner in the world.', 'Both Tom and Harry are slower than Peter.', 'Neither Tom nor Harry are the fastest runners.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Just because Tom is faster than Harry does not mean he is the fastest runner. Tom\'s ranking is only compared to Harry\'s, not to any other runners.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1947, 'Tom is a college student who is preparing for a Selective-Set-Express aptitude exam. He wants to divide his studying time equally among three subjects: Math, English, and Science. He has a total of 24 hours available each week for studying. If he spends 2 hours studying Math each day, how many hours does he have left each week to study English and Science?', '10 hours', '12 hours', '14 hours', '16 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Tom spends 2 hours studying Math each day, so he spends a total of 2 * 7 = 14 hours studying Math each week. Therefore, he has 24 - 14 = 10 hours left each week to study English and Science.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1948, 'Adam wants to buy a new laptop. He found two different models that he likes. The first model costs $800 and is on sale for 20% off, while the second model costs $1000 and is on sale for 25% off. Which laptop is cheaper?', 'The first model is cheaper.', 'The second model is cheaper.', 'Both models have the same price.', 'The prices cannot be determined based on the information given.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To compare the prices of the two models, we need to calculate the sale prices. For the first model, 20% of $800 is $160, so the sale price is $800 - $160 = $640. For the second model, 25% of $1000 is $250, so the sale price is $1000 - $250 = $750. Therefore, the first model is cheaper than the second model.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1949, 'Annie bought 3 different types of fruits: apples, bananas, and oranges. If she bought a total of 16 fruits and the number of bananas is half the number of apples, how many oranges did Annie buy?', '2', '4', '6', '8', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Let\'s assume the number of apples Annie bought is A. So, the number of bananas would be A/2. And since Annie bought a total of 16 fruits, we can write the equation A + A/2 + O = 16, where O represents the number of oranges. Simplifying the equation, we get 3A/2 + O = 16. Since A and O are integers, 3A/2 must also be an integer. The only way for this to happen is if A is even. Let\'s assume A = 4. Substituting the value of A in the equation, we get 3(4)/2 + O = 16, which simplifies to 6 + O = 16. Solving for O, we get O = 10/6. However, O must be an integer, so this assumption is incorrect. Now, let\'s assume A = 6. Substituting the value of A in the equation, we get 3(6)/2 + O = 16, which simplifies to 9 + O = 16. Solving for O, we get O = 7. Therefore, Annie bought 7 oranges.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1950, 'Oliver runs 5 km/h faster than Chris. If Oliver completes a 10 km race in 1 hour less than Chris, what is Chris\' average speed?', '5 km/h', '7.5 km/h', '10 km/h', '12.5 km/h', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Let\'s assume Chris\' average speed is S km/h. Since Oliver runs 5 km/h faster, his average speed would be S + 5 km/h. We know that Oliver completes the race in 1 hour less than Chris, so we can write the equation 10/(S + 5) + 1 = 10/S, where 10 represents the distance in km. Solving for S, we get S = 10 km/h. Therefore, Chris\' average speed is 10 km/h.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1951, 'Amelia invested a certain amount of money in two different savings accounts. The first account offers an annual interest rate of 4% and the second account offers an annual interest rate of 6%. If Amelia earns a total interest of $420 after one year and the interest earned from the second account is twice the interest earned from the first account, how much money did Amelia invest in each account?', '$2,000 in the first account and $4,000 in the second account', '$2,500 in the first account and $5,000 in the second account', '$3,000 in the first account and $6,000 in the second account', '$3,500 in the first account and $7,000 in the second account', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Let\'s assume Amelia invested X dollars in the first account and Y dollars in the second account. We know that the interest earned from the second account is twice the interest earned from the first account, so we can write the equation 0.04X + 0.06Y = 420. Simplifying the equation, we get 2(0.04X) + 0.06Y = 420, which further simplifies to 0.08X + 0.06Y = 420. Since the amount invested in the first account is X dollars, the amount invested in the second account is Y dollars. Therefore, the correct answer is option C: $3,000 in the first account and $6,000 in the second account.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1952, 'In a Selective-Set-Express competition, there are 5 participants: Clara, Chris, Daisy, Oliver, and Pia. Each participant can win a maximum of 2 medals, either gold or silver. If Daisy has won a gold medal, and Clara has won a silver medal, who among Oliver, Pia, and Chris could have also won a gold medal?', 'Oliver only', 'Pia only', 'Chris only', 'Both Oliver and Pia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Since Daisy has already won a gold medal and Clara has won a silver medal, there is only one gold medal left. Therefore, only one of the remaining participants (Oliver, Pia, or Chris) could have won a gold medal. The passage does not provide any information about Oliver or Pia, so it is possible for either of them to have won a gold medal. However, Clara has already won a silver medal, so Chris cannot have won a gold medal. Therefore, Chris is the only one among Oliver, Pia, and Chris who could have won a gold medal.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1953, 'During a Selective-Set-Express competition, each participant has to complete a set of 5 tasks. The participants are ranked based on their completion time, with the participant who finishes first ranked 1st. If Clara finished 3rd and Daisy finished after Oliver but before Chris, what is the highest possible rank that Oliver could have achieved?', '1st', '2nd', '3rd', '4th', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Based on the given information, Clara finished 3rd, so there are at least two participants who finished before Oliver. Daisy finished after Oliver but before Chris, so there is at least one participant who finished between Oliver and Chris. Therefore, the highest possible rank that Oliver could have achieved in this scenario is 3rd place.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1954, 'In a Selective-Set-Express event, participants are divided into two categories: Junior and Senior. The number of participants in the Junior category is always half the number of participants in the Senior category. If there are 60 participants in total, how many participants are in the Senior category?', '20', '30', '40', '50', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Let\'s assume the number of participants in the Senior category is x. Since the number of participants in the Junior category is always half the number of participants in the Senior category, the number of participants in the Junior category is x/2. The total number of participants is x + x/2 = 60. Solving this equation, we get x = 40. Therefore, there are 40 participants in the Senior category.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1955, 'During a Selective-Set-Express quiz competition, each contestant is asked 10 questions. Each correct answer is awarded 5 points, while each incorrect answer results in a deduction of 2 points. If Chris answered 8 questions correctly and 2 questions incorrectly, and Daisy answered 7 questions correctly and 3 questions incorrectly, who scored higher?', 'Chris', 'Daisy', 'Both scored the same', 'Cannot be determined', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'To calculate the score, we need to multiply the number of correct answers by 5 and subtract the number of incorrect answers multiplied by 2. Chris answered 8 questions correctly (8 * 5 = 40 points) and 2 questions incorrectly (2 * 2 = 4 points deduction). Therefore, Chris\'s final score is 40 - 4 = 36 points. Daisy answered 7 questions correctly (7 * 5 = 35 points) and 3 questions incorrectly (3 * 2 = 6 points deduction). Therefore, Daisy\'s final score is 35 - 6 = 29 points. Since Chris scored higher than Daisy, the correct answer is Daisy.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1956, 'In a Selective-Set-Express mathematics competition, each participant is required to solve 10 algebraic equations. Each correct equation leads to the addition of 4 points, while each incorrect equation results in a deduction of 2 points. If Pia solved 7 equations correctly and 3 equations incorrectly, and Oliver solved 8 equations correctly and 2 equations incorrectly, who had a higher score?', 'Pia', 'Oliver', 'Both scored the same', 'Cannot be determined', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'To calculate the score, we need to multiply the number of correct equations by 4 and subtract the number of incorrect equations multiplied by 2. Pia solved 7 equations correctly (7 * 4 = 28 points) and 3 equations incorrectly (3 * 2 = 6 points deduction). Therefore, Pia\'s final score is 28 - 6 = 22 points. Oliver solved 8 equations correctly (8 * 4 = 32 points) and 2 equations incorrectly (2 * 2 = 4 points deduction). Therefore, Oliver\'s final score is 32 - 4 = 28 points. Since Pia and Oliver have the same score, the correct answer is both scored the same.', 129, NULL, 0, 1),
(1957, 'David, Chris, and Lucy are roommates in a college dormitory. David has a sleeping schedule where he sleeps 6 hours a day. Chris sleeps 7 hours a day, and Lucy sleeps 8 hours a day. How many hours do all three of them sleep collectively in a week?', '119', '126', '133', '140', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The correct answer is (b) \'126.\' To find the total hours all three of them sleep collectively in a week, we need to find the sum of their individual sleeping hours. David sleeps for 6 hours/day, Chris sleeps for 7 hours/day, and Lucy sleeps for 8 hours/day. In a week (7 days), David sleeps 6 * 7 = 42 hours, Chris sleeps 7 * 7 = 49 hours, and Lucy sleeps 8 * 7 = 56 hours. Adding these together gives us a total of 42 + 49 + 56 = 147 hours. Therefore, all three of them sleep collectively for 126 hours in a week.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1958, 'David can type a 1000-word essay in 60 minutes. If Dennis types at 1.5 times the speed of David, how long will it take Dennis to type the same essay?', '24 min', '40 min', '48 min', '80 min', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'David can type 1000 words in 60 minutes. Since Dennis types at 1.5 times the speed of David, he can type 1500 words in the same time. Therefore, it will take Dennis 60 minutes to type a 1500-word essay. To find out how long it will take Dennis to type a 1000-word essay, we can use the proportion: 1500 words = 60 minutes, 1000 words = x minutes. Solving for x, we get x = (1000/1500)*60 = 40 minutes. Therefore, the answer is Option A.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1959, 'Nathan can paint a room in 6 hours. Jenson can paint the same room in 8 hours. How long will it take them to paint the room together?', '3 hours', '4 hours', '5 hours', '6 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The correct answer is (b) \'4 hours.\' Calculate the combined painting speed and use it to find the time needed to paint the room: (1/6) + (1/8) = 7/24. Taking the reciprocal of this value gives 24/7, which simplifies to approximately 3.43. Rounded up to the nearest whole number, the answer is 4 hours.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1960, 'Sarah and Alice are working together to complete a project. Sarah can complete 1/4 of the project in 2 hours, while Alice can complete 1/3 of the project in 3 hours. How long will it take both of them, working together, to complete the entire project?', '2 hours', '3 hours', '4 hours', '6 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Sarah can complete 1/4 of the project in 2 hours, so she can complete the entire project in 8 hours. Alice can complete 1/3 of the project in 3 hours, so she can complete the entire project in 9 hours. Working together, they can complete 1/8 + 1/9 of the project in 1 hour. To find out how long it will take them to complete the entire project, we can use the equation: 1/(1/8 + 1/9) = x. Solving for x, we get x = 1/((9+8)/72) = 72/17 ≈ 4.24 hours. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1961, 'Alice can complete a project in 12 days, while Myra can complete the same project in 18 days. If they work together for 6 days and then Myra leaves, how much longer will it take for Alice to complete the project?', '2 days', '4 days', '6 days', '8 days', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The correct answer is (b) \'4 days.\' Calculate the work rate of Alice and Myra and use it to find the remaining work to be done by Alice alone: (1/12) + (1/18) = 5/36. Multiplying this fraction by the number of days they worked together (6) gives 5/6. Subtracting this value from 1 (representing the completed work) gives 1 - 5/6 = 1/6. Taking the reciprocal of this fraction gives 6, indicating that Alice needs 6 days to complete 1/6th of the project. Therefore, she needs an additional 4 days to complete the remaining 5/6th of the project.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1962, 'In a coding competition, Oliver and Amelia solved 10 and 8 problems respectively. If Sam solved 25% more problems than Amelia, and Alice solved 50% more problems than Oliver, how many problems did they solve together?', '27 problems', '30 problems', '31 problems', '34 problems', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'The correct answer is (d) 34 problems. Calculate the number of problems solved together by summing the individual numbers: 10 + 8 + 8 + (25% of 8) + (50% of 10) = 34 problems.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1963, 'If Stella is studying late at night, then she will drink coffee. If Stella drinks coffee, then she won\'t be able to sleep. If Stella is studying late at night today, which of the following is not possible?', 'Stella will be able to sleep tonight', 'Stella is drinking coffee', 'Stella won\'t be able to sleep tonight', 'Stella will study late at night tomorrow', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The correct answer is (a) \'Stella will be able to sleep tonight.\' According to the given conditions, if Stella is studying late at night and drinks coffee, she won\'t be able to sleep.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1964, 'In a science competition, there are 5 participants: Tom, Dennis, Jessie, Alia, and Lisa. Tom finishes first and completes the experiment in 42 minutes. Dennis finishes in exactly half the time it takes Tom to complete. Jessie finishes in exactly one-fourth of the time it takes both Tom and Dennis together. Alia takes 25 minutes to complete the experiment. What is the average time it takes the participants to complete the experiment?', '19 mins', '20 mins', '21 mins', '22 mins', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Tom takes 42 minutes, Dennis takes half the time which is 42/2 = 21 minutes. Jessie takes one-fourth of the combined time of Tom and Dennis, so Jessie takes (42 + 21)/4 = 15.75 minutes. Alia takes 25 minutes to complete the experiment. Therefore, the average = (42 + 21 + 15.75 + 25)/5 = 20.15 minutes. Therefore, the answer is option C.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1965, 'If Bill eats spicy food, then he will sweat. If Bill is sweating, then he won\'t wear a jacket. If Bill is not wearing a jacket today, which of the following is not possible?', 'Bill ate spicy food', 'Bill is wearing a jacket', 'Bill will sweat', 'Bill won\'t eat spicy food tomorrow', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The correct answer is (b) \'Bill is wearing a jacket.\' According to the given conditions, if Bill is not wearing a jacket, it means he is sweating, and thus he won\'t wear a jacket.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1966, 'Oliver and Sam are participating in a running competition. Oliver completes the race in 40 minutes and Sam finishes in 32 minutes. If Alice finishes the race in exactly half the time it takes Oliver, and Amelia finishes in exactly two-thirds of the time it takes Sam, what is the average time taken by the runners?', '34 minutes', '36 minutes', '38 minutes', '40 minutes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The correct answer is (c) 38 minutes. Calculate the average time by summing the individual times and dividing by the number of runners: (40 + 20 + 32 + 21.33) / 4 = 38 minutes.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1967, 'Flora, Nora, and Sam are participating in a math competition. In the first round, they are given a set of 5 math problems to solve within a time limit of 30 minutes. Flora solves 3 problems correctly, Nora solves 2 problems correctly, and Sam solves 4 problems correctly. What is the probability that at least two of them solve the same number of problems correctly?', '0.525', '0.625', '0.725', '0.825', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'We need to find the probability that at least two of them solve the same number of problems correctly. There are three cases in which this can happen: (1) all three solve the same number of problems correctly, (2) two of them solve the same number of problems correctly while the third solves a different number, or (3) all three solve different numbers of problems correctly. We calculate the probability for each case and add them up to get the final probability. Case (1) is calculated as (5 choose 3) * (1/3)^3 * (2/3)^2. Case (2) is calculated as 3*(5 choose 2) * (1/3)^2 * (1/3) * (2/3)^2. Case (3) is calculated as (5 choose 1) * (1/3) * (1/3) * (1/3) * (2/3)^2. Adding up these individual probabilities gives us the desired probability.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1968, 'If David goes to the gym, then he will do weightlifting. If David does weightlifting, then he won\'t do cardio exercises. If David did weightlifting on Monday, which of the following is not possible?', 'David didn\'t go to the gym on Monday', 'David did cardio exercises on Tuesday', 'David did weightlifting on Wednesday', 'David didn\'t do weightlifting on Thursday', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'We know that if David does weightlifting, then he won\'t do cardio exercises. Since David did weightlifting on Monday, it is not possible for him to do weightlifting on Thursday.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1969, 'In a math exam, James scores 10% higher than Louis. Stella scores 20% lower than twice the score of James. If Louis scores 80 out of 100, how many marks does Stella score?', '60', '64', '68', '72', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Explanation for the correct answer', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1970, 'Amelia, Louis, and Stella are participating in a race. Louis finishes the race in 45 minutes and Amelia finishes the race in twice the time it takes Stella. If Stella finishes the race in 1 hour and 20 minutes, how long does Amelia take to finish the race?', '1 hour and 45 minutes', '2 hours and 15 minutes', '2 hours and 30 minutes', '2 hours and 40 minutes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Explanation for the correct answer', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1971, 'Amy, Ben, and Chloe are taking a college course in math. Amy has completed 10 out of 15 assignments, Ben has completed 12 out of 15 assignments, and Chloe has completed 8 out of 15 assignments. How many assignments have all three of them completed?', '5', '4', '3', '2', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'The correct answer is (c) \'3.\' To find the number of assignments that all three individuals have completed, we look for the intersection of their completed assignments. By comparing their completed assignment numbers, we can see that they have completed assignments numbered 10, 12, and 8. Therefore, all three of them have completed 3 assignments.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1972, 'Sam, Frank, Flora, and Nora are taking a multiple-choice exam with 10 questions. Each question has 4 possible options, and only one option is correct. If Sam and Frank each guess the answers randomly for all the questions, what is the probability that they both get at least 6 questions correct?', '0.085', '0.125', '0.215', '0.296', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'To find the probability that both Sam and Frank get at least 6 questions correct, we need to calculate the probability of each of them getting 6, 7, 8, 9, or 10 questions correct and then multiply them together. The probability of getting exactly 6 questions correct is (10 choose 6) * (0.25^6) * (0.75^4). Similarly, the probability of getting exactly 7, 8, 9, or 10 questions correct can be calculated using the binomial distribution formula. Adding up these individual probabilities gives us the probability that they both get at least 6 questions correct.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1973, 'Sally has a set of 5 numbers: {2, 4, 6, 8, 10}. She performs the following operations on the set: subtract 1 from each number, divide each number by 2, and then add 3 to each number. What is the sum of the numbers in the set after these operations?', '16', '18', '20', '22', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'After subtracting 1 from each number in the set, we have {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}. After dividing each number by 2, we have {0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5}. Finally, after adding 3 to each number, we have {3.5, 4.5, 5.5, 6.5, 7.5}. The sum of these numbers is 27.5, which rounds to 20. Therefore, the answer is Option C.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1974, 'If Marry is studying, then she will drink coffee. If Marry drinks coffee in the morning, then she won\'t drink coffee in the afternoon. If Marry drank coffee on Monday morning, which of the following is not possible?', 'Marry didn\'t study on Monday', 'Marry drank coffee on Monday afternoon', 'Marry didn\'t drink coffee on Tuesday morning', 'Marry drank coffee on Wednesday morning', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'We know that if Marry drinks coffee in the morning, then she won\'t drink coffee in the afternoon. Since Marry drank coffee on Monday morning, it is not possible for her to drink coffee on Tuesday morning.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1975, 'Natasha has a bag containing 8 red marbles, 5 blue marbles, and 3 yellow marbles. She randomly selects 2 marbles from the bag without replacement. What is the probability that she selects 1 red marble and 1 blue marble?', '0.099', '0.156', '0.234', '0.312', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The total number of marbles in the bag is 8 + 5 + 3 = 16. The probability of selecting 1 red marble from the bag is (8/16) * (5/15), since after selecting the first marble, there are 5 blue marbles left out of 15 marbles in total. Similarly, the probability of selecting 1 blue marble from the bag is (5/16) * (8/15). Adding these probabilities together, we get (8/16) * (5/15) + (5/16) * (8/15) = 40/240 + 40/240 = 80/240 = 1/3 = 0.333, which rounds to 0.156. Therefore, the answer is Option B.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1976, 'In a coding competition, there are 6 participants: Tom, Dennis, Jessie, Alia, Lisa, and Andrew. Tom finishes first and completes the task in 30 minutes. Dennis finishes in exactly half the time it takes Tom to complete. Jessie finishes in exactly one-third of the time it takes both Tom and Dennis together. Alia takes 40 minutes to complete the task. Lisa takes exactly twice the time it takes Andrew to complete the task. Andrew takes 25 minutes to complete the task. What is the average time it takes the participants to complete the task?', '28 mins', '29 mins', '30 mins', '31 mins', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'Tom takes 30 minutes, Dennis takes half the time which is 30/2 = 15 minutes. Jessie takes one-third of the combined time of Tom and Dennis, so Jessie takes (30 + 15)/3 = 15 minutes. Alia takes 40 minutes and Lisa takes twice the time of Andrew, so Lisa takes 2 * 25 = 50 minutes. Andrew takes 25 minutes to complete the task. Therefore, the average = (30 + 15 + 15 + 40 + 50 + 25)/6 = 27.5 minutes. Therefore, the answer is option D.', 130, NULL, 0, 1),
(1977, 'Science teacher: It is important to study and understand basic math concepts before moving on to advanced physics. Math serves as the foundation for many complex physics equations. \nSam: If I become a math expert, I will automatically excel in physics. \nWhich of the following best represents the mistake in Sam\'s reasoning?', 'Sam assumes that being a math expert guarantees success in physics.', 'Sam assumes that studying basic math is unnecessary for understanding advanced physics.', 'Sam assumes that math and physics are unrelated subjects.', 'Sam assumes that becoming a math expert requires no effort.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The mistake in Sam\'s reasoning is that he assumes that being a math expert guarantees success in physics. However, while a strong foundation in math is important for understanding physics, it does not guarantee automatic excellence in the subject. Therefore, the answer is Option A.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1978, 'Psychologist: Regular exercise has been shown to improve mental health and reduce symptoms of anxiety and depression. \nClara: If I start exercising for 30 minutes a day, my anxiety and depression will disappear completely. \nWhich of the following best represents the mistake in Clara\'s reasoning?', 'Clara assumes that exercising for 30 minutes a day will completely eliminate all symptoms of anxiety and depression.', 'Clara assumes that exercise has no impact on mental health.', 'Clara assumes that only medications can treat anxiety and depression.', 'Clara assumes that exercise is unnecessary for maintaining mental health.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The mistake in Clara\'s reasoning is that she assumes that exercising for 30 minutes a day will completely eliminate all symptoms of anxiety and depression. While regular exercise can have positive effects on mental health, it does not guarantee complete disappearance of symptoms. Therefore, the answer is Option A.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1979, 'Lucy bought a total of 50 books for her bookstore. If she spent $800 purchasing these books and each book cost $15, how much profit would she make if she sells each book for $20?', '$400', '$600', '$800', '$1000', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Lucy spent $800 on 50 books, so each book cost $800/50 = $16. If Lucy sells each book for $20, her profit per book is $20 - $16 = $4. Therefore, her total profit for selling 50 books is $4/book * 50 books = $200. However, the question asks for the profit, so we subtract the cost of purchasing the books from the profit, resulting in $200 - $800 = -$600. This means Lucy would make a loss of $600 instead of a profit.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1980, 'Philips wants to distribute 200 candies among his friends. If his friends consist of an equal number of boys and girls, and there are 30 boys in total, how many candies should each boy and girl receive?', '5', '6', '7', '8', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'If Philips has an equal number of boys and girls as friends, then there are also 30 girls. Therefore, the total number of friends is 30 boys + 30 girls = 60 friends. Since Philips wants to distribute 200 candies among his 60 friends, each friend should receive 200 candies / 60 friends = 3.33 candies (rounded to 2 decimal places). However, the question asks for the number of candies each boy and girl should receive, which should be an equal amount. Hence, each boy and girl should receive 3 candies.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1981, 'Evan and Jenson are playing a tennis match. The game starts at 2:30 PM and Evan scores a point every 6 minutes, while Jenson scores a point every 8 minutes. If Evan scores the first point, at what time will Jenson score the first point?', '2:54 PM', '3:06 PM', '3:12 PM', '3:15 PM', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The common multiple of 6 and 8 is 24. Therefore, Jenson will score the first point after 24 minutes, which is at 2:54 PM.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1982, 'Nora and Sally decide to walk together to a nearby park. Nora takes 15 minutes to walk from her house to the park, while Sally takes 18 minutes. If they both start walking at the same time and walk at a constant speed, how long will it take for them to meet at the park?', '27 minutes', '30 minutes', '36 minutes', '45 minutes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'The LCM of 15 and 18 is 90. Therefore, they will meet at the park after 90 minutes, which is 27 minutes from their starting time.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1983, 'All Olivers are Austins as are all Annies. Noras are not Olivers. If the above is true, which of the following is also true?', 'All Annies are Olivers', 'All Annies are Austins', 'All Austins are Olivers', 'All Noras are Annies', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'According to the given information, all Olivers are Austins. Since Noras are not Olivers, it is not true that all Noras are Annies. Therefore, the correct answer is that all Austins are Olivers.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1984, 'All Annies are Olivers and all Austins are Annies. Noras are not Annies. Based on the given information, which of the following is true?', 'All Noras are Austins', 'All Olivers are Noras', 'All Austins are Noras', 'All Annies are Austins', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '4', 'From the given information, we can conclude that all Annies are Olivers and all Austins are Annies. Therefore, it is true that all Annies are Austins.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1985, 'Flora had 9 different colored pens in her pencil case. How many pens does Flora need to pick out of her pencil case to guarantee that she has at least a pair of pens with the same color?', '4', '9', '10', '18', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Flora has to pick out 10 pens to guarantee she has at least one pair of pens with the same color as the greatest number of different, non-paired pens she can pick up is 9 as there are 9 different colored pens. Therefore, once she has picked out 9 different pens, the next pen she picks up will match at least one of the pens she has already picked up. Therefore, the correct answer is C.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1986, 'Chris has 7 different books on his bookshelf. In how many ways can Chris arrange the books if he wants to display 3 books at a time?', '35', '105', '210', '360', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Chris can arrange the 3 books out of the 7 different books on his bookshelf in 7P3 = (7!)/(7-3)! = (7*6*5)/(3*2*1) = 210 ways. Therefore, the correct answer is C.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1987, 'Flora and David are planning a road trip. Flora wants to drive 300 miles in 4 hours, while David wants to drive 400 miles in 6 hours. If they both drive at a constant speed, who will be driving faster?', 'Flora', 'David', 'They will be driving at the same speed', 'Cannot be determined', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'To determine who is driving faster, we need to calculate their speeds. Flora\'s speed is 300 miles / 4 hours = 75 miles per hour. David\'s speed is 400 miles / 6 hours = 66.67 miles per hour. Therefore, Flora will be driving faster.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1988, 'Amelia has a total of $500. She wants to divide this amount into two portions, one for savings and one for expenses. If she wants to save 40% of the total amount, how much money will she have for expenses?', '$200', '$250', '$300', '$350', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Amelia wants to save 40% of $500, which is $500 * 0.40 = $200. Therefore, she will have $500 - $200 = $300 for expenses.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1989, 'Flora, Sam, and Evan are competing in a race. Flora finishes the race in 12 seconds, while Sam finishes 2 seconds earlier than Evan. If the sum of their race times is 40 seconds, how long did Evan take to finish the race?', '10 seconds', '11 seconds', '13 seconds', '15 seconds', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', 'Let\'s represent Evan\'s race time as x. Since Flora finishes in 12 seconds, Sam finishes in (x + 2) seconds. The sum of their race times is 40 seconds, so we have the equation: 12 + x + (x + 2) = 40. Simplifying this equation gives us: 2x + 14 = 40. Solving for x gives us x = 13. Therefore, Evan took 13 seconds to finish the race, and the answer is option A.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1990, 'Myra, Evan, and Sam are assigned to complete a project together. Myra can finish the project in 8 hours, while Evan can finish it in 6 hours. If Sam also joins the project, they can complete it in 4 hours. How long would it take for Sam to complete the project on his own?', '12 hours', '16 hours', '18 hours', '24 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Let\'s represent the time it takes for Sam to complete the project on his own as x. We can create the equation: 1/8 + 1/6 + 1/x = 1/4 (representing their individual rates of work). To simplify this equation, we find the common denominator of 24x: 3x + 4x + 6 = 6x. Simplifying further gives us 13x = 24x. Solving for x gives us x = 16. Therefore, it would take Sam 16 hours to complete the project on his own, and the answer is option B.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1991, 'In a selective-mixed set of 15 numbers, Jessie is the median number. If Jessie is removed from the set, what effect does it have on the median?', 'The median increases', 'The median stays the same', 'The median decreases', 'The effect on the median cannot be determined', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'Since the median is the middle number in a set, removing one number from the set does not change the position of the remaining numbers. Therefore, the median stays the same.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1992, 'Bill spends a total of $480 on new clothes. He spends 30% of the total on pants and the rest on shirts. If he spends $90 more on shirts than on pants, how much does he spend on shirts?', '$210', '$240', '$270', '$300', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'Let\'s assume the amount spent on pants is x. Since Bill spends 30% of the total on pants, we can write the equation: 0.3 * 480 = x. Simplifying, we find that x = 144. Since he spends $90 more on shirts than on pants, the amount spent on shirts is x + 90 = 144 + 90 = 234. Therefore, Bill spends $234 on shirts.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1993, 'A class of college students took a math test, and their scores (out of 100) were as follows: Jenson - 85, Nora - 92, Sam - 78, and Georgia - 88. What is the average score for the class?', '83.25', '85', '88.25', '90.5', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', 'To find the average score, sum up the individual scores and divide by the number of students: (85 + 92 + 78 + 88) / 4 = 343 / 4 = 88.25. Therefore, the correct answer is option c.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1994, 'In a college library, there are 600 fiction books, 400 non-fiction books, and 200 reference books. If a student randomly selects a book from the library, what is the probability that it will be a non-fiction book?', '0.25', '0.33', '0.4', '0.5', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', 'The total number of books in the library is 600 + 400 + 200 = 1200. The probability of selecting a non-fiction book is given by the number of non-fiction books divided by the total number of books: 400 / 1200 = 1/3 = 0.33. Therefore, the correct answer is option b.', 131, NULL, 0, 1),
(1995, 'The following question consists of a set of three figures X, Y and Z showing a sequence of folding of a piece of paper. Fig (Z) shows the manner in which the folded paper has been cut. These three figures are followed by four answer figures from which you have to choose a figure which would most closely resemble the unfolded form fig. (Z).', '/NVImages/oImage/option_A_411705572587.png', '/NVImages/oImage/option_B_411705572587.png', '/NVImages/oImage/option_C_411705572587.png', '/NVImages/oImage/option_D_411705572587.png', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', NULL, 132, NULL, 1, 1),
